18¿é 12:17 He leads counselors away stripped, and makes fools of judges.
18¿é 12:18 He looses the sash of kings, and binds a waistcloth on their loins.
18¿é 12:19 He leads priests away stripped, and overthrows the mighty.
18¿é 12:20 He deprives of speech those who are trusted, and takes away the discernment of the elders.
18¿é 12:21 He pours contempt on princes, and looses the belt of the strong.
18¿é 12:22 He uncovers the deeps out of darkness, and brings deep darkness to light.
18¿é 12:23 He makes nations great, then destroys them; he enlarges nations, then leads them away.
18¿é 12:24 He strips understanding from the leaders of the earth, and makes them wander in a pathless waste.
18¿é 12:25 They grope in the dark without light; he makes them stagger like a drunkard.
18¿é 13:1 "Look, my eye has seen all this, my ear has heard and understood it.
18¿é 13:2 What you know, I also know; I am not inferior to you.
18¿é 13:3 But I would speak to the Almighty, and I desire to argue my case with God.
18¿é 13:4 As for you, you whitewash with lies; all of you are worthless physicians.
18¿é 13:5 If you would only keep silent, that would be your wisdom!
18¿é 13:6 Hear now my reasoning, and listen to the pleadings of my lips.
18¿é 13:7 Will you speak falsely for God, and speak deceitfully for him?
18¿é 13:8 Will you show partiality toward him, will you plead the case for God?
18¿é 13:9 Will it be well with you when he searches you out? Or can you deceive him, as one person deceives another?
18¿é 13:10 He will surely rebuke you if in secret you show partiality.
18¿é 13:11 Will not his majesty terrify you, and the dread of him fall upon you?
18¿é 13:12 Your maxims are proverbs of ashes, your defenses are defenses of clay.
18¿é 13:13 "Let me have silence, and I will speak, and let come on me what may.
18¿é 13:14 I will take my flesh in my teeth, and put my life in my hand.
18¿é 13:15 See, he will kill me; I have no hope; but I will defend my ways to his face.
18¿é 13:16 This will be my salvation, that the godless shall not come before him.
18¿é 13:17 Listen carefully to my words, and let my declaration be in your ears.
18¿é 13:18 I have indeed prepared my case; I know that I shall be vindicated.
18¿é 13:19 Who is there that will contend with me? For then I would be silent and die.
18¿é 13:20 Only grant two things to me, then I will not hide myself from your face:
18¿é 13:21 withdraw your hand far from me, and do not let dread of you terrify me.
18¿é 13:22 Then call, and I will answer; or let me speak, and you reply to me.
18¿é 13:23 How many are my iniquities and my sins? Make me know my transgression and my sin.
18¿é 13:24 Why do you hide your face, and count me as your enemy?
18¿é 13:25 Will you frighten a windblown leaf and pursue dry chaff?
18¿é 13:26 For you write bitter things against me, and make me reap the iniquities of my youth.
18¿é 13:27 You put my feet in the stocks, and watch all my paths; you set a bound to the soles of my feet.
18¿é 13:28 One wastes away like a rotten thing, like a garment that is moth-eaten.
18¿é 14:1 "A mortal, born of woman, few of days and full of trouble,
18¿é 14:2 comes up like a flower and withers, flees like a shadow and does not last.
18¿é 14:3 Do you fix your eyes on such a one? Do you bring me into judgment with you?
18¿é 14:4 Who can bring a clean thing out of an unclean? No one can.
18¿é 14:5 Since their days are determined, and the number of their months is known to you, and you have appointed the bounds that they cannot pass,
18¿é 14:6 look away from them, and desist, that they may enjoy, like laborers, their days.
18¿é 14:7 "For there is hope for a tree, if it is cut down, that it will sprout again, and that its shoots will not cease.
18¿é 14:8 Though its root grows old in the earth, and its stump dies in the ground,
18¿é 14:9 yet at the scent of water it will bud and put forth branches like a young plant.
18¿é 14:10 But mortals die, and are laid low; humans expire, and where are they?
18¿é 14:11 As waters fail from a lake, and a river wastes away and dries up,
18¿é 14:12 so mortals lie down and do not rise again; until the heavens are no more, they will not awake or be roused out of their sleep.
18¿é 14:13 Oh that you would hide me in Sheol, that you would conceal me until your wrath is past, that you would appoint me a set time, and remember me!
18¿é 14:14 If mortals die, will they live again? All the days of my service I would wait until my release should come.
18¿é 14:15 You would call, and I would answer you; you would long for the work of your hands.
18¿é 14:16 For then you would not number my steps, you would not keep watch over my sin;
18¿é 14:17 my transgression would be sealed up in a bag, and you would cover over my iniquity.
18¿é 14:18 "But the mountain falls and crumbles away, and the rock is removed from its place;
18¿é 14:19 the waters wear away the stones; the torrents wash away the soil of the earth; so you destroy the hope of mortals.
18¿é 14:20 You prevail forever against them, and they pass away; you change their countenance, and send them away.
18¿é 14:21 Their children come to honor, and they do not know it; they are brought low, and it goes unnoticed.
18¿é 14:22 They feel only the pain of their own bodies, and mourn only for themselves."
18¿é 15:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered:
18¿é 15:2 "Should the wise answer with windy knowledge, and fill themselves with the east wind?
18¿é 15:3 Should they argue in unprofitable talk, or in words with which they can do no good?
18¿é 15:4 But you are doing away with the fear of God, and hindering meditation before God.
18¿é 15:5 For your iniquity teaches your mouth, and you choose the tongue of the crafty.
18¿é 15:6 Your own mouth condemns you, and not I; your own lips testify against you.
18¿é 15:7 "Are you the firstborn of the human race? Were you brought forth before the hills?
18¿é 15:8 Have you listened in the council of God? And do you limit wisdom to yourself?
18¿é 15:9 What do you know that we do not know? What do you understand that is not clear to us?
18¿é 15:10 The gray-haired and the aged are on our side, those older than your father.
18¿é 15:11 Are the consolations of God too small for you, or the word that deals gently with you?
18¿é 15:12 Why does your heart carry you away, and why do your eyes flash,
18¿é 15:13 so that you turn your spirit against God, and let such words go out of your mouth?
18¿é 15:14 What are mortals, that they can be clean? Or those born of woman, that they can be righteous?
18¿é 15:15 God puts no trust even in his holy ones, and the heavens are not clean in his sight;
18¿é 15:16 how much less one who is abominable and corrupt, one who drinks iniquity like water!
18¿é 15:17 "I will show you; listen to me; what I have seen I will declare--
18¿é 15:18 what sages have told, and their ancestors have not hidden,
18¿é 15:19 to whom alone the land was given, and no stranger passed among them.
18¿é 15:20 The wicked writhe in pain all their days, through all the years that are laid up for the ruthless.
18¿é 15:21 Terrifying sounds are in their ears; in prosperity the destroyer will come upon them.
18¿é 15:22 They despair of returning from darkness, and they are destined for the sword.
18¿é 15:23 They wander abroad for bread, saying, 'Where is it?' They know that a day of darkness is ready at hand;
18¿é 15:24 distress and anguish terrify them; they prevail against them, like a king prepared for battle.
18¿é 15:25 Because they stretched out their hands against God, and bid defiance to the Almighty,
18¿é 15:26 running stubbornly against him with a thick-bossed shield;
18¿é 15:27 because they have covered their faces with their fat, and gathered fat upon their loins,
18¿é 15:28 they will live in desolate cities, in houses that no one should inhabit, houses destined to become heaps of ruins;
18¿é 15:29 they will not be rich, and their wealth will not endure, nor will they strike root in the earth;
18¿é 15:30 they will not escape from darkness; the flame will dry up their shoots, and their blossom will be swept away by the wind.
18¿é 15:31 Let them not trust in emptiness, deceiving themselves; for emptiness will be their recompense.
18¿é 15:32 It will be paid in full before their time, and their branch will not be green.
18¿é 15:33 They will shake off their unripe grape, like the vine, and cast off their blossoms, like the olive tree.
18¿é 15:34 For the company of the godless is barren, and fire consumes the tents of bribery.
18¿é 15:35 They conceive mischief and bring forth evil and their heart prepares deceit."
18¿é 16:1 Then Job answered:
18¿é 16:2 "I have heard many such things; miserable comforters are you all.
18¿é 16:3 Have windy words no limit? Or what provokes you that you keep on talking?
18¿é 16:4 I also could talk as you do, if you were in my place; I could join words together against you, and shake my head at you.
18¿é 16:5 I could encourage you with my mouth, and the solace of my lips would assuage your pain.
18¿é 16:6 "If I speak, my pain is not assuaged, and if I forbear, how much of it leaves me?
18¿é 16:7 Surely now God has worn me out; he has made desolate all my company.
18¿é 16:8 And he has shriveled me up, which is a witness against me; my leanness has risen up against me, and it testifies to my face.
18¿é 16:9 He has torn me in his wrath, and hated me; he has gnashed his teeth at me; my adversary sharpens his eyes against me.
18¿é 16:10 They have gaped at me with their mouths; they have struck me insolently on the cheek; they mass themselves together against me.
18¿é 16:11 God gives me up to the ungodly, and casts me into the hands of the wicked.
18¿é 16:12 I was at ease, and he broke me in two; he seized me by the neck and dashed me to pieces; he set me up as his target;
18¿é 16:13 his archers surround me. He slashes open my kidneys, and shows no mercy; he pours out my gall on the ground.
18¿é 16:14 He bursts upon me again and again; he rushes at me like a warrior.
18¿é 16:15 I have sewed sackcloth upon my skin, and have laid my strength in the dust.
18¿é 16:16 My face is red with weeping, and deep darkness is on my eyelids,
18¿é 16:17 though there is no violence in my hands, and my prayer is pure.
18¿é 16:18 "O earth, do not cover my blood; let my outcry find no resting place.
18¿é 16:19 Even now, in fact, my witness is in heaven, and he that vouches for me is on high.
18¿é 16:20 My friends scorn me; my eye pours out tears to God,
18¿é 16:21 that he would maintain the right of a mortal with God, as one does for a neighbor.
18¿é 16:22 For when a few years have come, I shall go the way from which I shall not return.
18¿é 17:1 My spirit is broken, my days are extinct, the grave is ready for me.
18¿é 17:2 Surely there are mockers around me, and my eye dwells on their provocation.
18¿é 17:3 "Lay down a pledge for me with yourself; who is there that will give surety for me?
18¿é 17:4 Since you have closed their minds to understanding, therefore you will not let them triumph.
18¿é 17:5 Those who denounce friends for reward--the eyes of their children will fail.
18¿é 17:6 "He has made me a byword of the peoples, and I am one before whom people spit.
18¿é 17:7 My eye has grown dim from grief, and all my members are like a shadow.
18¿é 17:8 The upright are appalled at this, and the innocent stir themselves up against the godless.
18¿é 17:9 Yet the righteous hold to their way, and they that have clean hands grow stronger and stronger.
18¿é 17:10 But you, come back now, all of you, and I shall not find a sensible person among you.
18¿é 17:11 My days are past, my plans are broken off, the desires of my heart.
18¿é 17:12 They make night into day; 'The light,' they say, 'is near to the darkness.'
18¿é 17:13 If I look for Sheol as my house, if I spread my couch in darkness,
18¿é 17:14 if I say to the Pit, 'You are my father,' and to the worm, 'My mother,' or 'My sister,'
18¿é 17:15 where then is my hope? Who will see my hope?
18¿é 17:16 Will it go down to the bars of Sheol? Shall we descend together into the dust?"
18¿é 18:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite answered:
18¿é 18:2 "How long will you hunt for words? Consider, and then we shall speak.
18¿é 18:3 Why are we counted as cattle? Why are we stupid in your sight?
18¿é 18:4 You who tear yourself in your anger--shall the earth be forsaken because of you, or the rock be removed out of its place?
18¿é 18:5 "Surely the light of the wicked is put out, and the flame of their fire does not shine.
18¿é 18:6 The light is dark in their tent, and the lamp above them is put out.
18¿é 18:7 Their strong steps are shortened, and their own schemes throw them down.
18¿é 18:8 For they are thrust into a net by their own feet, and they walk into a pitfall.
18¿é 18:9 A trap seizes them by the heel; a snare lays hold of them.
18¿é 18:10 A rope is hid for them in the ground, a trap for them in the path.
18¿é 18:11 Terrors frighten them on every side, and chase them at their heels.
18¿é 18:12 Their strength is consumed by hunger, and calamity is ready for their stumbling.
18¿é 18:13 By disease their skin is consumed, the firstborn of Death consumes their limbs.
18¿é 18:14 They are torn from the tent in which they trusted, and are brought to the king of terrors.
18¿é 18:15 In their tents nothing remains; sulfur is scattered upon their habitations.
18¿é 18:16 Their roots dry up beneath, and their branches wither above.
18¿é 18:17 Their memory perishes from the earth, and they have no name in the street.
18¿é 18:18 They are thrust from light into darkness, and driven out of the world.
18¿é 18:19 They have no offspring or descendant among their people, and no survivor where they used to live.
18¿é 18:20 They of the west are appalled at their fate, and horror seizes those of the east.
18¿é 18:21 Surely such are the dwellings of the ungodly, such is the place of those who do not know God."
18¿é 19:1 Then Job answered:
18¿é 19:2 "How long will you torment me, and break me in pieces with words?
18¿é 19:3 These ten times you have cast reproach upon me; are you not ashamed to wrong me?
18¿é 19:4 And even if it is true that I have erred, my error remains with me.
18¿é 19:5 If indeed you magnify yourselves against me, and make my humiliation an argument against me,
18¿é 19:6 know then that God has put me in the wrong, and closed his net around me.
18¿é 19:7 Even when I cry out, 'Violence!' I am not answered; I call aloud, but there is no justice.
18¿é 19:8 He has walled up my way so that I cannot pass, and he has set darkness upon my paths.
18¿é 19:9 He has stripped my glory from me, and taken the crown from my head.
18¿é 19:10 He breaks me down on every side, and I am gone, he has uprooted my hope like a tree.
18¿é 19:11 He has kindled his wrath against me, and counts me as his adversary.
18¿é 19:12 His troops come on together; they have thrown up siegeworks against me, and encamp around my tent.
18¿é 19:13 "He has put my family far from me, and my acquaintances are wholly estranged from me.
18¿é 19:14 My relatives and my close friends have failed me;
18¿é 19:15 the guests in my house have forgotten me; my serving girls count me as a stranger; I have become an alien in their eyes.
18¿é 19:16 I call to my servant, but he gives me no answer; I must myself plead with him.
18¿é 19:17 My breath is repulsive to my wife; I am loathsome to my own family.
18¿é 19:18 Even young children despise me; when I rise, they talk against me.
18¿é 19:19 All my intimate friends abhor me, and those whom I loved have turned against me.
18¿é 19:20 My bones cling to my skin and to my flesh, and I have escaped by the skin of my teeth.
18¿é 19:21 Have pity on me, have pity on me, O you my friends, for the hand of God has touched me!
18¿é 19:22 Why do you, like God, pursue me, never satisfied with my flesh?
18¿é 19:23 "O that my words were written down! O that they were inscribed in a book!
18¿é 19:24 O that with an iron pen and with lead they were engraved on a rock forever!
18¿é 19:25 For I know that my Redeemer lives, and that at the last he will stand upon the earth;
18¿é 19:26 and after my skin has been thus destroyed, then in my flesh I shall see God,
18¿é 19:27 whom I shall see on my side, and my eyes shall behold, and not another. My heart faints within me!
18¿é 19:28 If you say, 'How we will persecute him!' and, 'The root of the matter is found in him';
18¿é 19:29 be afraid of the sword, for wrath brings the punishment of the sword, so that you may know there is a judgment."
18¿é 20:1 Then Zophar the Naamathite answered:
18¿é 20:2 "Pay attention! My thoughts urge me to answer, because of the agitation within me.
18¿é 20:3 I hear censure that insults me, and a spirit beyond my understanding answers me.
18¿é 20:4 Do you not know this from of old, ever since mortals were placed on earth,
18¿é 20:5 that the exulting of the wicked is short, and the joy of the godless is but for a moment?
18¿é 20:6 Even though they mount up high as the heavens, and their head reaches to the clouds,
18¿é 20:7 they will perish forever like their own dung; those who have seen them will say, 'Where are they?'
18¿é 20:8 They will fly away like a dream, and not be found; they will be chased away like a vision of the night.
18¿é 20:9 The eye that saw them will see them no more, nor will their place behold them any longer.
18¿é 20:10 Their children will seek the favor of the poor, and their hands will give back their wealth.
18¿é 20:11 Their bodies, once full of youth, will lie down in the dust with them.
18¿é 20:12 "Though wickedness is sweet in their mouth, though they hide it under their tongues,
18¿é 20:13 though they are loath to let it go, and hold it in their mouths,
18¿é 20:14 yet their food is turned in their stomachs; it is the venom of asps within them.
18¿é 20:15 They swallow down riches and vomit them up again; God casts them out of their bellies.
18¿é 20:16 They will suck the poison of asps; the tongue of a viper will kill them.
18¿é 20:17 They will not look on the rivers, the streams flowing with honey and curds.
18¿é 20:18 They will give back the fruit of their toil, and will not swallow it down; from the profit of their trading they will get no enjoyment.
18¿é 20:19 For they have crushed and abandoned the poor, they have seized a house that they did not build.
18¿é 20:20 "They knew no quiet in their bellies; in their greed they let nothing escape.
18¿é 20:21 There was nothing left after they had eaten; therefore their prosperity will not endure.
18¿é 20:22 In full sufficiency they will be in distress; all the force of misery will come upon them.
18¿é 20:23 To fill their belly to the full God will send his fierce anger into them, and rain it upon them as their food.
18¿é 20:24 They will flee from an iron weapon; a bronze arrow will strike them through.
18¿é 20:25 It is drawn forth and comes out of their body, and the glittering point comes out of their gall; terrors come upon them.
18¿é 20:26 Utter darkness is laid up for their treasures; a fire fanned by no one will devour them; what is left in their tent will be consumed.
18¿é 20:27 The heavens will reveal their iniquity, and the earth will rise up against them.
18¿é 20:28 The possessions of their house will be carried away, dragged off in the day of God's wrath.
18¿é 20:29 This is the portion of the wicked from God, the heritage decreed for them by God."
18¿é 21:1 Then Job answered:
18¿é 21:2 "Listen carefully to my words, and let this be your consolation.
18¿é 21:3 Bear with me, and I will speak; then after I have spoken, mock on.
18¿é 21:4 As for me, is my complaint addressed to mortals? Why should I not be impatient?
18¿é 21:5 Look at me, and be appalled, and lay your hand upon your mouth.
18¿é 21:6 When I think of it I am dismayed, and shuddering seizes my flesh.
18¿é 21:7 Why do the wicked live on, reach old age, and grow mighty in power?
18¿é 21:8 Their children are established in their presence, and their offspring before their eyes.
18¿é 21:9 Their houses are safe from fear, and no rod of God is upon them.
18¿é 21:10 Their bull breeds without fail; their cow calves and never miscarries.
18¿é 21:11 They send out their little ones like a flock, and their children dance around.
18¿é 21:12 They sing to the tambourine and the lyre, and rejoice to the sound of the pipe.
18¿é 21:13 They spend their days in prosperity, and in peace they go down to Sheol.
18¿é 21:14 They say to God, 'Leave us alone! We do not desire to know your ways.
18¿é 21:15 What is the Almighty, that we should serve him? And what profit do we get if we pray to him?'
18¿é 21:16 Is not their prosperity indeed their own achievement? The plans of the wicked are repugnant to me.
18¿é 21:17 "How often is the lamp of the wicked put out? How often does calamity come upon them? How often does God distribute pains in his anger?
18¿é 21:18 How often are they like straw before the wind, and like chaff that the storm carries away?
18¿é 21:19 You say, 'God stores up their iniquity for their children.' Let it be paid back to them, so that they may know it.
18¿é 21:20 Let their own eyes see their destruction, and let them drink of the wrath of the Almighty.
18¿é 21:21 For what do they care for their household after them, when the number of their months is cut off?
18¿é 21:22 Will any teach God knowledge, seeing that he judges those that are on high?
18¿é 21:23 One dies in full prosperity, being wholly at ease and secure,
18¿é 21:24 his loins full of milk and the marrow of his bones moist.
18¿é 21:25 Another dies in bitterness of soul, never having tasted of good.
18¿é 21:26 They lie down alike in the dust, and the worms cover them.
18¿é 21:27 "Oh, I know your thoughts, and your schemes to wrong me.
18¿é 21:28 For you say, 'Where is the house of the prince? Where is the tent in which the wicked lived?'
18¿é 21:29 Have you not asked those who travel the roads, and do you not accept their testimony,
18¿é 21:30 that the wicked are spared in the day of calamity, and are rescued in the day of wrath?
18¿é 21:31 Who declares their way to their face, and who repays them for what they have done?
18¿é 21:32 When they are carried to the grave, a watch is kept over their tomb.
18¿é 21:33 The clods of the valley are sweet to them; everyone will follow after, and those who went before are innumerable.
18¿é 21:34 How then will you comfort me with empty nothings? There is nothing left of your answers but falsehood."
18¿é 22:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered:
18¿é 22:2 "Can a mortal be of use to God? Can even the wisest be of service to him?
18¿é 22:3 Is it any pleasure to the Almighty if you are righteous, or is it gain to him if you make your ways blameless?
18¿é 22:4 Is it for your piety that he reproves you, and enters into judgment with you?
18¿é 22:5 Is not your wickedness great? There is no end to your iniquities.
18¿é 22:6 For you have exacted pledges from your family for no reason, and stripped the naked of their clothing.
18¿é 22:7 You have given no water to the weary to drink, and you have withheld bread from the hungry.
18¿é 22:8 The powerful possess the land, and the favored live in it.
18¿é 22:9 You have sent widows away empty-handed, and the arms of the orphans you have crushed.
18¿é 22:10 Therefore snares are around you, and sudden terror overwhelms you,
18¿é 22:11 or darkness so that you cannot see; a flood of water covers you.
18¿é 22:12 "Is not God high in the heavens? See the highest stars, how lofty they are!
18¿é 22:13 Therefore you say, 'What does God know? Can he judge through the deep darkness?
18¿é 22:14 Thick clouds enwrap him, so that he does not see, and he walks on the dome of heaven.'
18¿é 22:15 Will you keep to the old way that the wicked have trod?
18¿é 22:16 They were snatched away before their time; their foundation was washed away by a flood.
18¿é 22:17 They said to God, 'Leave us alone,' and 'What can the Almighty do to us?'
18¿é 22:18 Yet he filled their houses with good things--but the plans of the wicked are repugnant to me.
18¿é 22:19 The righteous see it and are glad; the innocent laugh them to scorn,
18¿é 22:20 saying, 'Surely our adversaries are cut off, and what they left, the fire has consumed.'
18¿é 22:21 "Agree with God, and be at peace; in this way good will come to you.
18¿é 22:22 Receive instruction from his mouth, and lay up his words in your heart.
18¿é 22:23 If you return to the Almighty, you will be restored, if you remove unrighteousness from your tents,
18¿é 22:24 if you treat gold like dust, and gold of Ophir like the stones of the torrent-bed,
18¿é 22:25 and if the Almighty is your gold and your precious silver,
18¿é 22:26 then you will delight yourself in the Almighty, and lift up your face to God.
18¿é 22:27 You will pray to him, and he will hear you, and you will pay your vows.
18¿é 22:28 You will decide on a matter, and it will be established for you, and light will shine on your ways.
18¿é 22:29 When others are humiliated, you say it is pride; for he saves the humble.
18¿é 22:30 He will deliver even those who are guilty; they will escape because of the cleanness of your hands."
18¿é 23:1 Then Job answered:
18¿é 23:2 "Today also my complaint is bitter; his hand is heavy despite my groaning.
18¿é 23:3 Oh, that I knew where I might find him, that I might come even to his dwelling!
18¿é 23:4 I would lay my case before him, and fill my mouth with arguments.
18¿é 23:5 I would learn what he would answer me, and understand what he would say to me.
18¿é 23:6 Would he contend with me in the greatness of his power? No; but he would give heed to me.
18¿é 23:7 There an upright person could reason with him, and I should be acquitted forever by my judge.
18¿é 23:8 "If I go forward, he is not there; or backward, I cannot perceive him;
18¿é 23:9 on the left he hides, and I cannot behold him; I turn to the right, but I cannot see him.
18¿é 23:10 But he knows the way that I take; when he has tested me, I shall come out like gold.
18¿é 23:11 My foot has held fast to his steps; I have kept his way and have not turned aside.
18¿é 23:12 I have not departed from the commandment of his lips; I have treasured in my bosom the words of his mouth.
18¿é 23:13 But he stands alone and who can dissuade him? What he desires, that he does.
18¿é 23:14 For he will complete what he appoints for me; and many such things are in his mind.
18¿é 23:15 Therefore I am terrified at his presence; when I consider, I am in dread of him.
18¿é 23:16 God has made my heart faint; the Almighty has terrified me;
18¿é 23:17 If only I could vanish in darkness, and thick darkness would cover my face!
18¿é 24:1 "Why are times not kept by the Almighty, and why do those who know him never see his days?
18¿é 24:2 The wicked remove landmarks; they seize flocks and pasture them.
18¿é 24:3 They drive away the donkey of the orphan; they take the widow's ox for a pledge.
18¿é 24:4 They thrust the needy off the road; the poor of the earth all hide themselves.
18¿é 24:5 Like wild asses in the desert they go out to their toil, scavenging in the wasteland food for their young.
18¿é 24:6 They reap in a field not their own and they glean in the vineyard of the wicked.
18¿é 24:7 They lie all night naked, without clothing, and have no covering in the cold.
18¿é 24:8 They are wet with the rain of the mountains, and cling to the rock for want of shelter.
18¿é 24:9 "There are those who snatch the orphan child from the breast, and take as a pledge the infant of the poor.
18¿é 24:10 They go about naked, without clothing; though hungry, they carry the sheaves;
18¿é 24:11 between their terraces they press out oil; they tread the wine presses, but suffer thirst.
18¿é 24:12 From the city the dying groan, and the throat of the wounded cries for help; yet God pays no attention to their prayer.
18¿é 24:13 "There are those who rebel against the light, who are not acquainted with its ways, and do not stay in its paths.
18¿é 24:14 The murderer rises at dusk to kill the poor and needy, and in the night is like a thief.
18¿é 24:15 The eye of the adulterer also waits for the twilight, saying, 'No eye will see me'; and he disguises his face.
18¿é 24:16 In the dark they dig through houses; by day they shut themselves up; they do not know the light.
18¿é 24:17 For deep darkness is morning to all of them; for they are friends with the terrors of deep darkness.
18¿é 24:18 "Swift are they on the face of the waters; their portion in the land is cursed; no treader turns toward their vineyards.
18¿é 24:19 Drought and heat snatch away the snow waters; so does Sheol those who have sinned.
18¿é 24:20 The womb forgets them; the worm finds them sweet; they are no longer remembered; so wickedness is broken like a tree.
18¿é 24:21 "They harm the childless woman, and do no good to the widow.
18¿é 24:22 Yet God prolongs the life of the mighty by his power; they rise up when they despair of life.
18¿é 24:23 He gives them security, and they are supported; his eyes are upon their ways.
18¿é 24:24 They are exalted a little while, and then are gone; they wither and fade like the mallow; they are cut off like the heads of grain.
18¿é 24:25 If it is not so, who will prove me a liar, and show that there is nothing in what I say?"
18¿é 25:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite answered:
