18¿é 25:5 If even the moon is not bright and the stars are not pure in his sight,
18¿é 25:6 how much less a mortal, who is a maggot, and a human being, who is a worm!"
18¿é 26:1 Then Job answered:
18¿é 26:2 "How you have helped one who has no power! How you have assisted the arm that has no strength!
18¿é 26:3 How you have counseled one who has no wisdom, and given much good advice!
18¿é 26:4 With whose help have you uttered words, and whose spirit has come forth from you?
18¿é 26:5 The shades below tremble, the waters and their inhabitants.
18¿é 26:6 Sheol is naked before God, and Abaddon has no covering.
18¿é 26:7 He stretches out Zaphon over the void, and hangs the earth upon nothing.
18¿é 26:8 He binds up the waters in his thick clouds, and the cloud is not torn open by them.
18¿é 26:9 He covers the face of the full moon, and spreads over it his cloud.
18¿é 26:10 He has described a circle on the face of the waters, at the boundary between light and darkness.
18¿é 26:11 The pillars of heaven tremble, and are astounded at his rebuke.
18¿é 26:12 By his power he stilled the Sea; by his understanding he struck down Rahab.
18¿é 26:13 By his wind the heavens were made fair; his hand pierced the fleeing serpent.
18¿é 26:14 These are indeed but the outskirts of his ways; and how small a whisper do we hear of him! But the thunder of his power who can understand?"
18¿é 27:1 Job again took up his discourse and said:
18¿é 27:2 "As God lives, who has taken away my right, and the Almighty, who has made my soul bitter,
18¿é 27:3 as long as my breath is in me and the spirit of God is in my nostrils,
18¿é 27:4 my lips will not speak falsehood, and my tongue will not utter deceit.
18¿é 27:5 Far be it from me to say that you are right; until I die I will not put away my integrity from me.
18¿é 27:6 I hold fast my righteousness, and will not let it go; my heart does not reproach me for any of my days.
18¿é 27:7 "May my enemy be like the wicked, and may my opponent be like the unrighteous.
18¿é 27:8 For what is the hope of the godless when God cuts them off, when God takes away their lives?
18¿é 27:9 Will God hear their cry when trouble comes upon them?
18¿é 27:10 Will they take delight in the Almighty? Will they call upon God at all times?
18¿é 27:11 I will teach you concerning the hand of God; that which is with the Almighty I will not conceal.
18¿é 27:12 All of you have seen it yourselves; why then have you become altogether vain?
18¿é 27:13 "This is the portion of the wicked with God, and the heritage that oppressors receive from the Almighty:
18¿é 27:14 If their children are multiplied, it is for the sword; and their offspring have not enough to eat.
18¿é 27:15 Those who survive them the pestilence buries, and their widows make no lamentation.
18¿é 27:16 Though they heap up silver like dust, and pile up clothing like clay--
