18¿é 27:18 They build their houses like nests, like booths made by sentinels of the vineyard.
18¿é 27:19 They go to bed with wealth, but will do so no more; they open their eyes, and it is gone.
18¿é 27:20 Terrors overtake them like a flood; in the night a whirlwind carries them off.
18¿é 27:21 The east wind lifts them up and they are gone; it sweeps them out of their place.
18¿é 27:22 It hurls at them without pity; they flee from its power in headlong flight.
18¿é 27:23 It claps its hands at them, and hisses at them from its place.
18¿é 28:1 "Surely there is a mine for silver, and a place for gold to be refined.
18¿é 28:2 Iron is taken out of the earth, and copper is smelted from ore.
18¿é 28:3 Miners put an end to darkness, and search out to the farthest bound the ore in gloom and deep darkness.
18¿é 28:4 They open shafts in a valley away from human habitation; they are forgotten by travelers, they sway suspended, remote from people.
18¿é 28:5 As for the earth, out of it comes bread; but underneath it is turned up as by fire.
18¿é 28:6 Its stones are the place of sapphires, and its dust contains gold.
18¿é 28:7 "That path no bird of prey knows, and the falcon's eye has not seen it.
18¿é 28:8 The proud wild animals have not trodden it; the lion has not passed over it.
18¿é 28:9 "They put their hand to the flinty rock, and overturn mountains by the roots.
18¿é 28:10 They cut out channels in the rocks, and their eyes see every precious thing.
18¿é 28:11 The sources of the rivers they probe; hidden things they bring to light.
18¿é 28:12 "But where shall wisdom be found? And where is the place of understanding?
18¿é 28:13 Mortals do not know the way to it, and it is not found in the land of the living.
18¿é 28:14 The deep says, 'It is not in me,' and the sea says, 'It is not with me.'
18¿é 28:15 It cannot be gotten for gold, and silver cannot be weighed out as its price.
18¿é 28:16 It cannot be valued in the gold of Ophir, in precious onyx or sapphire.
18¿é 28:17 Gold and glass cannot equal it, nor can it be exchanged for jewels of fine gold.
18¿é 28:18 No mention shall be made of coral or of crystal; the price of wisdom is above pearls.
18¿é 28:19 The chrysolite of Ethiopia cannot compare with it, nor can it be valued in pure gold.
18¿é 28:20 "Where then does wisdom come from? And where is the place of understanding?
18¿é 28:21 It is hidden from the eyes of all living, and concealed from the birds of the air.
18¿é 28:22 Abaddon and Death say, 'We have heard a rumor of it with our ears.'
18¿é 28:23 "God understands the way to it, and he knows its place.
18¿é 28:24 For he looks to the ends of the earth, and sees everything under the heavens.
18¿é 28:25 When he gave to the wind its weight, and apportioned out the waters by measure;
18¿é 28:26 when he made a decree for the rain, and a way for the thunderbolt;
18¿é 28:27 then he saw it and declared it; he established it, and searched it out.
18¿é 28:28 And he said to humankind, 'Truly, the fear of the Lord, that is wisdom; and to depart from evil is understanding.'"
18¿é 29:1 Job again took up his discourse and said:
18¿é 29:2 "Oh, that I were as in the months of old, as in the days when God watched over me;
18¿é 29:3 when his lamp shone over my head, and by his light I walked through darkness;
18¿é 29:4 when I was in my prime, when the friendship of God was upon my tent;
18¿é 29:5 when the Almighty was still with me, when my children were around me;
18¿é 29:6 when my steps were washed with milk, and the rock poured out for me streams of oil!
18¿é 29:7 When I went out to the gate of the city, when I took my seat in the square,
18¿é 29:8 the young men saw me and withdrew, and the aged rose up and stood;
18¿é 29:9 the nobles refrained from talking, and laid their hands on their mouths;
18¿é 29:10 the voices of princes were hushed, and their tongues stuck to the roof of their mouths.
18¿é 29:11 When the ear heard, it commended me, and when the eye saw, it approved;
18¿é 29:12 because I delivered the poor who cried, and the orphan who had no helper.
18¿é 29:13 The blessing of the wretched came upon me, and I caused the widow's heart to sing for joy.
18¿é 29:14 I put on righteousness, and it clothed me; my justice was like a robe and a turban.
18¿é 29:15 I was eyes to the blind, and feet to the lame.
18¿é 29:16 I was a father to the needy, and I championed the cause of the stranger.
18¿é 29:17 I broke the fangs of the unrighteous, and made them drop their prey from their teeth.
18¿é 29:18 Then I thought, 'I shall die in my nest, and I shall multiply my days like the phoenix;
18¿é 29:19 my roots spread out to the waters, with the dew all night on my branches;
18¿é 29:20 my glory was fresh with me, and my bow ever new in my hand.'
18¿é 29:21 "They listened to me, and waited, and kept silence for my counsel.
18¿é 29:22 After I spoke they did not speak again, and my word dropped upon them like dew.
18¿é 29:23 They waited for me as for the rain; they opened their mouths as for the spring rain.
18¿é 29:24 I smiled on them when they had no confidence; and the light of my countenance they did not extinguish.
18¿é 29:25 I chose their way, and sat as chief, and I lived like a king among his troops, like one who comforts mourners.
18¿é 30:1 "But now they make sport of me, those who are younger than I, whose fathers I would have disdained to set with the dogs of my flock.
18¿é 30:2 What could I gain from the strength of their hands? All their vigor is gone.
18¿é 30:3 Through want and hard hunger they gnaw the dry and desolate ground,
18¿é 30:4 they pick mallow and the leaves of bushes, and to warm themselves the roots of broom.
18¿é 30:5 They are driven out from society; people shout after them as after a thief.
18¿é 30:6 In the gullies of wadis they must live, in holes in the ground, and in the rocks.
18¿é 30:7 Among the bushes they bray; under the nettles they huddle together.
18¿é 30:8 A senseless, disreputable brood, they have been whipped out of the land.
18¿é 30:9 "And now they mock me in song; I am a byword to them.
18¿é 30:10 They abhor me, they keep aloof from me; they do not hesitate to spit at the sight of me.
18¿é 30:11 Because God has loosed my bowstring and humbled me, they have cast off restraint in my presence.
18¿é 30:12 On my right hand the rabble rise up; they send me sprawling, and build roads for my ruin.
18¿é 30:13 They break up my path, they promote my calamity; no one restrains them.
18¿é 30:14 As through a wide breach they come; amid the crash they roll on.
18¿é 30:15 Terrors are turned upon me; my honor is pursued as by the wind, and my prosperity has passed away like a cloud.
18¿é 30:16 "And now my soul is poured out within me; days of affliction have taken hold of me.
18¿é 30:17 The night racks my bones, and the pain that gnaws me takes no rest.
18¿é 30:18 With violence he seizes my garment; he grasps me by the collar of my tunic.
18¿é 30:19 He has cast me into the mire, and I have become like dust and ashes.
18¿é 30:20 I cry to you and you do not answer me; I stand, and you merely look at me.
18¿é 30:21 You have turned cruel to me; with the might of your hand you persecute me.
18¿é 30:22 You lift me up on the wind, you make me ride on it, and you toss me about in the roar of the storm.
18¿é 30:23 I know that you will bring me to death, and to the house appointed for all living.
18¿é 30:24 "Surely one does not turn against the needy, when in disaster they cry for help.
18¿é 30:25 Did I not weep for those whose day was hard? Was not my soul grieved for the poor?
18¿é 30:26 But when I looked for good, evil came; and when I waited for light, darkness came.
18¿é 30:27 My inward parts are in turmoil, and are never still; days of affliction come to meet me.
18¿é 30:28 I go about in sunless gloom; I stand up in the assembly and cry for help.
18¿é 30:29 I am a brother of jackals, and a companion of ostriches.
18¿é 30:30 My skin turns black and falls from me, and my bones burn with heat.
18¿é 30:31 My lyre is turned to mourning, and my pipe to the voice of those who weep.
18¿é 31:1 "I have made a covenant with my eyes; how then could I look upon a virgin?
18¿é 31:2 What would be my portion from God above, and my heritage from the Almighty on high?
18¿é 31:3 Does not calamity befall the unrighteous, and disaster the workers of iniquity?
18¿é 31:4 Does he not see my ways, and number all my steps?
18¿é 31:5 "If I have walked with falsehood, and my foot has hurried to deceit--
18¿é 31:6 let me be weighed in a just balance, and let God know my integrity!--
18¿é 31:7 if my step has turned aside from the way, and my heart has followed my eyes, and if any spot has clung to my hands;
18¿é 31:8 then let me sow, and another eat; and let what grows for me be rooted out.
18¿é 31:9 "If my heart has been enticed by a woman, and I have lain in wait at my neighbor's door;
18¿é 31:10 then let my wife grind for another, and let other men kneel over her.
18¿é 31:11 For that would be a heinous crime; that would be a criminal offense;
18¿é 31:12 for that would be a fire consuming down to Abaddon, and it would burn to the root all my harvest.
18¿é 31:13 "If I have rejected the cause of my male or female slaves, when they brought a complaint against me;
