18¿é 31:15 Did not he who made me in the womb make them? And did not one fashion us in the womb?
18¿é 31:16 "If I have withheld anything that the poor desired, or have caused the eyes of the widow to fail,
18¿é 31:17 or have eaten my morsel alone, and the orphan has not eaten from it--
18¿é 31:18 for from my youth I reared the orphan like a father, and from my mother's womb I guided the widow--
18¿é 31:19 if I have seen anyone perish for lack of clothing, or a poor person without covering,
18¿é 31:20 whose loins have not blessed me, and who was not warmed with the fleece of my sheep;
18¿é 31:21 if I have raised my hand against the orphan, because I saw I had supporters at the gate;
18¿é 31:22 then let my shoulder blade fall from my shoulder, and let my arm be broken from its socket.
18¿é 31:23 For I was in terror of calamity from God, and I could not have faced his majesty.
18¿é 31:24 "If I have made gold my trust, or called fine gold my confidence;
18¿é 31:25 if I have rejoiced because my wealth was great, or because my hand had gotten much;
18¿é 31:26 if I have looked at the sun when it shone, or the moon moving in splendor,
18¿é 31:27 and my heart has been secretly enticed, and my mouth has kissed my hand;
18¿é 31:28 this also would be an iniquity to be punished by the judges, for I should have been false to God above.
18¿é 31:29 "If I have rejoiced at the ruin of those who hated me, or exulted when evil overtook them--
18¿é 31:30 I have not let my mouth sin by asking for their lives with a curse--
18¿é 31:31 if those of my tent ever said, 'O that we might be sated with his flesh!'--
18¿é 31:32 the stranger has not lodged in the street; I have opened my doors to the traveler--
18¿é 31:33 if I have concealed my transgressions as others do, by hiding my iniquity in my bosom,
18¿é 31:34 because I stood in great fear of the multitude, and the contempt of families terrified me, so that I kept silence, and did not go out of doors--
18¿é 31:35 Oh, that I had one to hear me! (Here is my signature! let the Almighty answer me!) Oh, that I had the indictment written by my adversary!
18¿é 31:36 Surely I would carry it on my shoulder; I would bind it on me like a crown;
18¿é 31:37 I would give him an account of all my steps; like a prince I would approach him.
18¿é 31:38 "If my land has cried out against me, and its furrows have wept together;
18¿é 31:39 if I have eaten its yield without payment, and caused the death of its owners;
18¿é 31:40 let thorns grow instead of wheat, and foul weeds instead of barley." The words of Job are ended.
18¿é 32:1 So these three men ceased to answer Job, because he was righteous in his own eyes.
18¿é 32:2 Then Elihu son of Barachel the Buzite, of the family of Ram, became angry. He was angry at Job because he justified himself rather than God;
18¿é 32:3 he was angry also at Job's three friends because they had found no answer, though they had declared Job to be in the wrong.
18¿é 32:4 Now Elihu had waited to speak to Job, because they were older than he.
18¿é 32:5 But when Elihu saw that there was no answer in the mouths of these three men, he became angry.
18¿é 32:6 Elihu son of Barachel the Buzite answered: "I am young in years, and you are aged; therefore I was timid and afraid to declare my opinion to you.
18¿é 32:7 I said, 'Let days speak, and many years teach wisdom.'
18¿é 32:8 But truly it is the spirit in a mortal, the breath of the Almighty, that makes for understanding.
18¿é 32:9 It is not the old that are wise, nor the aged that understand what is right.
18¿é 32:10 Therefore I say, 'Listen to me; let me also declare my opinion.'
18¿é 32:11 "See, I waited for your words, I listened for your wise sayings, while you searched out what to say.
18¿é 32:12 I gave you my attention, but there was in fact no one that confuted Job, no one among you that answered his words.
18¿é 32:13 Yet do not say, 'We have found wisdom; God may vanquish him, not a human.'
18¿é 32:14 He has not directed his words against me, and I will not answer him with your speeches.
18¿é 32:15 "They are dismayed, they answer no more; they have not a word to say.
18¿é 32:16 And am I to wait, because they do not speak, because they stand there, and answer no more?
18¿é 32:17 I also will give my answer; I also will declare my opinion.
18¿é 32:18 For I am full of words; the spirit within me constrains me.
18¿é 32:19 My heart is indeed like wine that has no vent; like new wineskins, it is ready to burst.
18¿é 32:20 I must speak, so that I may find relief; I must open my lips and answer.
18¿é 32:21 I will not show partiality to any person or use flattery toward anyone.
18¿é 32:22 For I do not know how to flatter--or my Maker would soon put an end to me!
18¿é 33:1 "But now, hear my speech, O Job, and listen to all my words.
18¿é 33:2 See, I open my mouth; the tongue in my mouth speaks.
18¿é 33:3 My words declare the uprightness of my heart, and what my lips know they speak sincerely.
18¿é 33:4 The spirit of God has made me, and the breath of the Almighty gives me life.
18¿é 33:5 Answer me, if you can; set your words in order before me; take your stand.
18¿é 33:6 See, before God I am as you are; I too was formed from a piece of clay.
18¿é 33:7 No fear of me need terrify you; my pressure will not be heavy on you.
18¿é 33:8 "Surely, you have spoken in my hearing, and I have heard the sound of your words.
18¿é 33:9 You say, 'I am clean, without transgression; I am pure, and there is no iniquity in me.
18¿é 33:10 Look, he finds occasions against me, he counts me as his enemy;
18¿é 33:11 he puts my feet in the stocks, and watches all my paths.'
18¿é 33:12 "But in this you are not right. I will answer you: God is greater than any mortal.
18¿é 33:13 Why do you contend against him, saying, 'He will answer none of my words'?
18¿é 33:14 For God speaks in one way, and in two, though people do not perceive it.
18¿é 33:15 In a dream, in a vision of the night, when deep sleep falls on mortals, while they slumber on their beds,
18¿é 33:16 then he opens their ears, and terrifies them with warnings,
18¿é 33:17 that he may turn them aside from their deeds, and keep them from pride,
18¿é 33:18 to spare their souls from the Pit, their lives from traversing the River.
18¿é 33:19 They are also chastened with pain upon their beds, and with continual strife in their bones,
18¿é 33:20 so that their lives loathe bread, and their appetites dainty food.
18¿é 33:21 Their flesh is so wasted away that it cannot be seen; and their bones, once invisible, now stick out.
18¿é 33:22 Their souls draw near the Pit, and their lives to those who bring death.
18¿é 33:23 Then, if there should be for one of them an angel, a mediator, one of a thousand, one who declares a person upright,
18¿é 33:24 and he is gracious to that person, and says, 'Deliver him from going down into the Pit; I have found a ransom;
18¿é 33:25 let his flesh become fresh with youth; let him return to the days of his youthful vigor.'
18¿é 33:26 Then he prays to God, and is accepted by him, he comes into his presence with joy, and God repays him for his righteousness.
18¿é 33:27 That person sings to others and says, 'I sinned, and perverted what was right, and it was not paid back to me.
18¿é 33:28 He has redeemed my soul from going down to the Pit, and my life shall see the light.'
18¿é 33:29 "God indeed does all these things, twice, three times, with mortals,
18¿é 33:30 to bring back their souls from the Pit, so that they may see the light of life.
18¿é 33:31 Pay heed, Job, listen to me; be silent, and I will speak.
18¿é 33:32 If you have anything to say, answer me; speak, for I desire to justify you.
18¿é 33:33 If not, listen to me; be silent, and I will teach you wisdom."
18¿é 34:1 Then Elihu continued and said:
18¿é 34:2 "Hear my words, you wise men, and give ear to me, you who know;
18¿é 34:3 for the ear tests words as the palate tastes food.
18¿é 34:4 Let us choose what is right; let us determine among ourselves what is good.
18¿é 34:5 For Job has said, 'I am innocent, and God has taken away my right;
18¿é 34:6 in spite of being right I am counted a liar; my wound is incurable, though I am without transgression.'
18¿é 34:7 Who is there like Job, who drinks up scoffing like water,
18¿é 34:8 who goes in company with evildoers and walks with the wicked?
18¿é 34:9 For he has said, 'It profits one nothing to take delight in God.'
18¿é 34:10 "Therefore, hear me, you who have sense, far be it from God that he should do wickedness, and from the Almighty that he should do wrong.
18¿é 34:11 For according to their deeds he will repay them, and according to their ways he will make it befall them.
18¿é 34:12 Of a truth, God will not do wickedly, and the Almighty will not pervert justice.
18¿é 34:13 Who gave him charge over the earth and who laid on him the whole world?
18¿é 34:14 If he should take back his spirit to himself, and gather to himself his breath,
18¿é 34:15 all flesh would perish together, and all mortals return to dust.
18¿é 34:16 "If you have understanding, hear this; listen to what I say.
18¿é 34:17 Shall one who hates justice govern? Will you condemn one who is righteous and mighty,
18¿é 34:18 who says to a king, 'You scoundrel!' and to princes, 'You wicked men!';
18¿é 34:19 who shows no partiality to nobles, nor regards the rich more than the poor, for they are all the work of his hands?
18¿é 34:20 In a moment they die; at midnight the people are shaken and pass away, and the mighty are taken away by no human hand.
18¿é 34:21 "For his eyes are upon the ways of mortals, and he sees all their steps.
18¿é 34:22 There is no gloom or deep darkness where evildoers may hide themselves.
18¿é 34:23 For he has not appointed a time for anyone to go before God in judgment.
18¿é 34:24 He shatters the mighty without investigation, and sets others in their place.
18¿é 34:25 Thus, knowing their works, he overturns them in the night, and they are crushed.
18¿é 34:26 He strikes them for their wickedness while others look on,
18¿é 34:27 because they turned aside from following him, and had no regard for any of his ways,
18¿é 34:28 so that they caused the cry of the poor to come to him, and he heard the cry of the afflicted--
18¿é 34:29 When he is quiet, who can condemn? When he hides his face, who can behold him, whether it be a nation or an individual?--
18¿é 34:30 so that the godless should not reign, or those who ensnare the people.
18¿é 34:31 "For has anyone said to God, 'I have endured punishment; I will not offend any more;
18¿é 34:32 teach me what I do not see; if I have done iniquity, I will do it no more'?
18¿é 34:33 Will he then pay back to suit you, because you reject it? For you must choose, and not I; therefore declare what you know.
18¿é 34:34 Those who have sense will say to me, and the wise who hear me will say,
18¿é 34:35 'Job speaks without knowledge, his words are without insight.'
18¿é 34:36 Would that Job were tried to the limit, because his answers are those of the wicked.
18¿é 34:37 For he adds rebellion to his sin; he claps his hands among us, and multiplies his words against God."
18¿é 35:1 Elihu continued and said:
18¿é 35:2 "Do you think this to be just? You say, 'I am in the right before God.'
18¿é 35:3 If you ask, 'What advantage have I? How am I better off than if I had sinned?'
18¿é 35:4 I will answer you and your friends with you.
18¿é 35:5 Look at the heavens and see; observe the clouds, which are higher than you.
18¿é 35:6 If you have sinned, what do you accomplish against him? And if your transgressions are multiplied, what do you do to him?
18¿é 35:7 If you are righteous, what do you give to him; or what does he receive from your hand?
18¿é 35:8 Your wickedness affects others like you, and your righteousness, other human beings.
18¿é 35:9 "Because of the multitude of oppressions people cry out; they call for help because of the arm of the mighty.
18¿é 35:10 But no one says, 'Where is God my Maker, who gives strength in the night,
18¿é 35:11 who teaches us more than the animals of the earth, and makes us wiser than the birds of the air?'
18¿é 35:12 There they cry out, but he does not answer, because of the pride of evildoers.
18¿é 35:13 Surely God does not hear an empty cry, nor does the Almighty regard it.
18¿é 35:14 How much less when you say that you do not see him, that the case is before him, and you are waiting for him!
18¿é 35:15 And now, because his anger does not punish, and he does not greatly heed transgression,
18¿é 35:16 Job opens his mouth in empty talk, he multiplies words without knowledge."
18¿é 36:1 Elihu continued and said:
18¿é 36:2 "Bear with me a little, and I will show you, for I have yet something to say on God's behalf.
18¿é 36:3 I will bring my knowledge from far away, and ascribe righteousness to my Maker.
18¿é 36:4 For truly my words are not false; one who is perfect in knowledge is with you.
18¿é 36:5 "Surely God is mighty and does not despise any; he is mighty in strength of understanding.
18¿é 36:6 He does not keep the wicked alive, but gives the afflicted their right.
18¿é 36:7 He does not withdraw his eyes from the righteous, but with kings on the throne he sets them forever, and they are exalted.
