18¿é 38:1 Then the LORD answered Job out of the whirlwind:
18¿é 38:2 "Who is this that darkens counsel by words without knowledge?
18¿é 38:3 Gird up your loins like a man, I will question you, and you shall declare to me.
18¿é 38:4 "Where were you when I laid the foundation of the earth? Tell me, if you have understanding.
18¿é 38:5 Who determined its measurements--surely you know! Or who stretched the line upon it?
18¿é 38:6 On what were its bases sunk, or who laid its cornerstone
18¿é 38:7 when the morning stars sang together and all the heavenly beings shouted for joy?
18¿é 38:8 "Or who shut in the sea with doors when it burst out from the womb?--
18¿é 38:9 when I made the clouds its garment, and thick darkness its swaddling band,
18¿é 38:10 and prescribed bounds for it, and set bars and doors,
18¿é 38:11 and said, 'Thus far shall you come, and no farther, and here shall your proud waves be stopped'?
18¿é 38:12 "Have you commanded the morning since your days began, and caused the dawn to know its place,
18¿é 38:13 so that it might take hold of the skirts of the earth, and the wicked be shaken out of it?
18¿é 38:14 It is changed like clay under the seal, and it is dyed like a garment.
18¿é 38:15 Light is withheld from the wicked, and their uplifted arm is broken.
18¿é 38:16 "Have you entered into the springs of the sea, or walked in the recesses of the deep?
18¿é 38:17 Have the gates of death been revealed to you, or have you seen the gates of deep darkness?
18¿é 38:18 Have you comprehended the expanse of the earth? Declare, if you know all this.
18¿é 38:19 "Where is the way to the dwelling of light, and where is the place of darkness,
18¿é 38:20 that you may take it to its territory and that you may discern the paths to its home?
18¿é 38:21 Surely you know, for you were born then, and the number of your days is great!
18¿é 38:22 "Have you entered the storehouses of the snow, or have you seen the storehouses of the hail,
18¿é 38:23 which I have reserved for the time of trouble, for the day of battle and war?
18¿é 38:24 What is the way to the place where the light is distributed, or where the east wind is scattered upon the earth?
18¿é 38:25 "Who has cut a channel for the torrents of rain, and a way for the thunderbolt,
18¿é 38:26 to bring rain on a land where no one lives, on the desert, which is empty of human life,
18¿é 38:27 to satisfy the waste and desolate land, and to make the ground put forth grass?
18¿é 38:28 "Has the rain a father, or who has begotten the drops of dew?
18¿é 38:29 From whose womb did the ice come forth, and who has given birth to the hoarfrost of heaven?
18¿é 38:30 The waters become hard like stone, and the face of the deep is frozen.
18¿é 38:31 "Can you bind the chains of the Pleiades, or loose the cords of Orion?
18¿é 38:32 Can you lead forth the Mazzaroth in their season, or can you guide the Bear with its children?
18¿é 38:33 Do you know the ordinances of the heavens? Can you establish their rule on the earth?
18¿é 38:34 "Can you lift up your voice to the clouds, so that a flood of waters may cover you?
18¿é 38:35 Can you send forth lightnings, so that they may go and say to you, 'Here we are'?
18¿é 38:36 Who has put wisdom in the inward parts, or given understanding to the mind?
18¿é 38:37 Who has the wisdom to number the clouds? Or who can tilt the waterskins of the heavens,
18¿é 38:38 when the dust runs into a mass and the clods cling together?
18¿é 38:39 "Can you hunt the prey for the lion, or satisfy the appetite of the young lions,
18¿é 38:40 when they crouch in their dens, or lie in wait in their covert?
18¿é 38:41 Who provides for the raven its prey, when its young ones cry to God, and wander about for lack of food?
18¿é 39:1 "Do you know when the mountain goats give birth? Do you observe the calving of the deer?
18¿é 39:2 Can you number the months that they fulfill, and do you know the time when they give birth,
18¿é 39:3 when they crouch to give birth to their offspring, and are delivered of their young?
18¿é 39:4 Their young ones become strong, they grow up in the open; they go forth, and do not return to them.
18¿é 39:5 "Who has let the wild ass go free? Who has loosed the bonds of the swift ass,
18¿é 39:6 to which I have given the steppe for its home, the salt land for its dwelling place?
18¿é 39:7 It scorns the tumult of the city; it does not hear the shouts of the driver.
18¿é 39:8 It ranges the mountains as its pasture, and it searches after every green thing.
18¿é 39:9 "Is the wild ox willing to serve you? Will it spend the night at your crib?
18¿é 39:10 Can you tie it in the furrow with ropes, or will it harrow the valleys after you?
18¿é 39:11 Will you depend on it because its strength is great, and will you hand over your labor to it?
18¿é 39:12 Do you have faith in it that it will return, and bring your grain to your threshing floor?
18¿é 39:13 "The ostrich's wings flap wildly, though its pinions lack plumage.
18¿é 39:14 For it leaves its eggs to the earth, and lets them be warmed on the ground,
18¿é 39:15 forgetting that a foot may crush them, and that a wild animal may trample them.
18¿é 39:16 It deals cruelly with its young, as if they were not its own; though its labor should be in vain, yet it has no fear;
18¿é 39:17 because God has made it forget wisdom, and given it no share in understanding.
18¿é 39:18 When it spreads its plumes aloft, it laughs at the horse and its rider.
18¿é 39:19 "Do you give the horse its might? Do you clothe its neck with mane?
18¿é 39:20 Do you make it leap like the locust? Its majestic snorting is terrible.
18¿é 39:21 It paws violently, exults mightily; it goes out to meet the weapons.
18¿é 39:22 It laughs at fear, and is not dismayed; it does not turn back from the sword.
18¿é 39:23 Upon it rattle the quiver, the flashing spear, and the javelin.
18¿é 39:24 With fierceness and rage it swallows the ground; it cannot stand still at the sound of the trumpet.
18¿é 39:25 When the trumpet sounds, it says 'Aha!' From a distance it smells the battle, the thunder of the captains, and the shouting.
18¿é 39:26 "Is it by your wisdom that the hawk soars, and spreads its wings toward the south?
18¿é 39:27 Is it at your command that the eagle mounts up and makes its nest on high?
18¿é 39:28 It lives on the rock and makes its home in the fastness of the rocky crag.
18¿é 39:29 From there it spies the prey; its eyes see it from far away.
18¿é 39:30 Its young ones suck up blood; and where the slain are, there it is."
18¿é 40:1 And the LORD said to Job:
18¿é 40:2 "Shall a faultfinder contend with the Almighty? Anyone who argues with God must respond."
18¿é 40:3 Then Job answered the LORD:
18¿é 40:4 "See, I am of small account; what shall I answer you? I lay my hand on my mouth.
18¿é 40:5 I have spoken once, and I will not answer; twice, but will proceed no further."
18¿é 40:6 Then the LORD answered Job out of the whirlwind:
18¿é 40:7 "Gird up your loins like a man; I will question you, and you declare to me.
18¿é 40:8 Will you even put me in the wrong? Will you condemn me that you may be justified?
18¿é 40:9 Have you an arm like God, and can you thunder with a voice like his?
18¿é 40:10 "Deck yourself with majesty and dignity; clothe yourself with glory and splendor.
18¿é 40:11 Pour out the overflowings of your anger, and look on all who are proud, and abase them.
18¿é 40:12 Look on all who are proud, and bring them low; tread down the wicked where they stand.
18¿é 40:13 Hide them all in the dust together; bind their faces in the world below.
18¿é 40:14 Then I will also acknowledge to you that your own right hand can give you victory.
18¿é 40:15 "Look at Behemoth, which I made just as I made you; it eats grass like an ox.
18¿é 40:16 Its strength is in its loins, and its power in the muscles of its belly.
18¿é 40:17 It makes its tail stiff like a cedar; the sinews of its thighs are knit together.
18¿é 40:18 Its bones are tubes of bronze, its limbs like bars of iron.
18¿é 40:19 "It is the first of the great acts of God--only its Maker can approach it with the sword.
18¿é 40:20 For the mountains yield food for it where all the wild animals play.
18¿é 40:21 Under the lotus plants it lies, in the covert of the reeds and in the marsh.
18¿é 40:22 The lotus trees cover it for shade; the willows of the wadi surround it.
18¿é 40:23 Even if the river is turbulent, it is not frightened; it is confident though Jordan rushes against its mouth.
18¿é 40:24 Can one take it with hooks or pierce its nose with a snare?
18¿é 41:1 "Can you draw out Leviathan with a fishhook, or press down its tongue with a cord?
18¿é 41:2 Can you put a rope in its nose, or pierce its jaw with a hook?
18¿é 41:3 Will it make many supplications to you? Will it speak soft words to you?
18¿é 41:4 Will it make a covenant with you to be taken as your servant forever?
18¿é 41:5 Will you play with it as with a bird, or will you put it on leash for your girls?
18¿é 41:6 Will traders bargain over it? Will they divide it up among the merchants?
18¿é 41:7 Can you fill its skin with harpoons, or its head with fishing spears?
18¿é 41:8 Lay hands on it; think of the battle; you will not do it again!
18¿é 41:9 Any hope of capturing it will be disappointed; were not even the gods overwhelmed at the sight of it?
18¿é 41:10 No one is so fierce as to dare to stir it up. Who can stand before it?
18¿é 41:11 Who can confront it and be safe? --under the whole heaven, who?
18¿é 41:12 "I will not keep silence concerning its limbs, or its mighty strength, or its splendid frame.
18¿é 41:13 Who can strip off its outer garment? Who can penetrate its double coat of mail?
18¿é 41:14 Who can open the doors of its face? There is terror all around its teeth.
18¿é 41:15 Its back is made of shields in rows, shut up closely as with a seal.
18¿é 41:16 One is so near to another that no air can come between them.
18¿é 41:17 They are joined one to another; they clasp each other and cannot be separated.
18¿é 41:18 Its sneezes flash forth light, and its eyes are like the eyelids of the dawn.
18¿é 41:19 From its mouth go flaming torches; sparks of fire leap out.
18¿é 41:20 Out of its nostrils comes smoke, as from a boiling pot and burning rushes.
18¿é 41:21 Its breath kindles coals, and a flame comes out of its mouth.
18¿é 41:22 In its neck abides strength, and terror dances before it.
18¿é 41:23 The folds of its flesh cling together; it is firmly cast and immovable.
18¿é 41:24 Its heart is as hard as stone, as hard as the lower millstone.
18¿é 41:25 When it raises itself up the gods are afraid; at the crashing they are beside themselves.
18¿é 41:26 Though the sword reaches it, it does not avail, nor does the spear, the dart, or the javelin.
18¿é 41:27 It counts iron as straw, and bronze as rotten wood.
18¿é 41:28 The arrow cannot make it flee; slingstones, for it, are turned to chaff.
18¿é 41:29 Clubs are counted as chaff; it laughs at the rattle of javelins.
18¿é 41:30 Its underparts are like sharp potsherds; it spreads itself like a threshing sledge on the mire.
18¿é 41:31 It makes the deep boil like a pot; it makes the sea like a pot of ointment.
18¿é 41:32 It leaves a shining wake behind it; one would think the deep to be white-haired.
18¿é 41:33 On earth it has no equal, a creature without fear.
18¿é 41:34 It surveys everything that is lofty; it is king over all that are proud."
18¿é 42:1 Then Job answered the LORD:
18¿é 42:2 "I know that you can do all things, and that no purpose of yours can be thwarted.
18¿é 42:3 'Who is this that hides counsel without knowledge?' Therefore I have uttered what I did not understand, things too wonderful for me, which I did not know.
18¿é 42:4 'Hear, and I will speak; I will question you, and you declare to me.'
18¿é 42:5 I had heard of you by the hearing of the ear, but now my eye sees you;
18¿é 42:6 therefore I despise myself, and repent in dust and ashes."
18¿é 42:7 After the LORD had spoken these words to Job, the LORD said to Eliphaz the Temanite: "My wrath is kindled against you and against your two friends; for you have not spoken of me what is right, as my servant Job has.
18¿é 42:8 Now therefore take seven bulls and seven rams, and go to my servant Job, and offer up for yourselves a burnt offering; and my servant Job shall pray for you, for I will accept his prayer not to deal with you according to your folly; for you have not spoken of me what is right, as my servant Job has done."
18¿é 42:9 So Eliphaz the Temanite and Bildad the Shuhite and Zophar the Naamathite went and did what the LORD had told them; and the LORD accepted Job's prayer.
