19½Ã 76:1 To the leader: with stringed instruments. A Psalm of Asaph. A Song. In Judah God is known, his name is great in Israel.
19½Ã 76:2 His abode has been established in Salem, his dwelling place in Zion.
19½Ã 76:3 There he broke the flashing arrows, the shield, the sword, and the weapons of war. Selah
19½Ã 76:4 Glorious are you, more majestic than the everlasting mountains.
19½Ã 76:5 The stouthearted were stripped of their spoil; they sank into sleep; none of the troops was able to lift a hand.
19½Ã 76:6 At your rebuke, O God of Jacob, both rider and horse lay stunned.
19½Ã 76:7 But you indeed are awesome! Who can stand before you when once your anger is roused?
19½Ã 76:8 From the heavens you uttered judgment; the earth feared and was still
19½Ã 76:9 when God rose up to establish judgment, to save all the oppressed of the earth. Selah
19½Ã 76:10 Human wrath serves only to praise you, when you bind the last bit of your wrath around you.
19½Ã 76:11 Make vows to the LORD your God, and perform them; let all who are around him bring gifts to the one who is awesome,
19½Ã 76:12 who cuts off the spirit of princes, who inspires fear in the kings of the earth.
19½Ã 77:1 To the leader: according to Jeduthun. Of Asaph. A Psalm. I cry aloud to God, aloud to God, that he may hear me.
19½Ã 77:2 In the day of my trouble I seek the Lord; in the night my hand is stretched out without wearying; my soul refuses to be comforted.
19½Ã 77:3 I think of God, and I moan; I meditate, and my spirit faints. Selah
19½Ã 77:4 You keep my eyelids from closing; I am so troubled that I cannot speak.
19½Ã 77:5 I consider the days of old, and remember the years of long ago.
19½Ã 77:6 I commune with my heart in the night; I meditate and search my spirit:
19½Ã 77:7 "Will the Lord spurn forever, and never again be favorable?
19½Ã 77:8 Has his steadfast love ceased forever? Are his promises at an end for all time?
19½Ã 77:9 Has God forgotten to be gracious? Has he in anger shut up his compassion?" Selah
19½Ã 77:10 And I say, "It is my grief that the right hand of the Most High has changed."
19½Ã 77:11 I will call to mind the deeds of the LORD; I will remember your wonders of old.
19½Ã 77:12 I will meditate on all your work, and muse on your mighty deeds.
19½Ã 77:13 Your way, O God, is holy. What god is so great as our God?
19½Ã 77:14 You are the God who works wonders; you have displayed your might among the peoples.
19½Ã 77:15 With your strong arm you redeemed your people, the descendants of Jacob and Joseph. Selah
19½Ã 77:16 When the waters saw you, O God, when the waters saw you, they were afraid; the very deep trembled.
19½Ã 77:17 The clouds poured out water; the skies thundered; your arrows flashed on every side.
19½Ã 77:18 The crash of your thunder was in the whirlwind; your lightnings lit up the world; the earth trembled and shook.
19½Ã 77:19 Your way was through the sea, your path, through the mighty waters; yet your footprints were unseen.
19½Ã 77:20 You led your people like a flock by the hand of Moses and Aaron.
19½Ã 78:1 A Maskil of Asaph. Give ear, O my people, to my teaching; incline your ears to the words of my mouth.
19½Ã 78:2 I will open my mouth in a parable; I will utter dark sayings from of old,
19½Ã 78:3 things that we have heard and known, that our ancestors have told us.
19½Ã 78:4 We will not hide them from their children; we will tell to the coming generation the glorious deeds of the LORD, and his might, and the wonders that he has done.
19½Ã 78:5 He established a decree in Jacob, and appointed a law in Israel, which he commanded our ancestors to teach to their children;
19½Ã 78:6 that the next generation might know them, the children yet unborn, and rise up and tell them to their children,
19½Ã 78:7 so that they should set their hope in God, and not forget the works of God, but keep his commandments;
19½Ã 78:8 and that they should not be like their ancestors, a stubborn and rebellious generation, a generation whose heart was not steadfast, whose spirit was not faithful to God.
19½Ã 78:9 The Ephraimites, armed with the bow, turned back on the day of battle.
19½Ã 78:10 They did not keep God's covenant, but refused to walk according to his law.
19½Ã 78:11 They forgot what he had done, and the miracles that he had shown them.
19½Ã 78:12 In the sight of their ancestors he worked marvels in the land of Egypt, in the fields of Zoan.
19½Ã 78:13 He divided the sea and let them pass through it, and made the waters stand like a heap.
19½Ã 78:14 In the daytime he led them with a cloud, and all night long with a fiery light.
19½Ã 78:15 He split rocks open in the wilderness, and gave them drink abundantly as from the deep.
19½Ã 78:16 He made streams come out of the rock, and caused waters to flow down like rivers.
19½Ã 78:17 Yet they sinned still more against him, rebelling against the Most High in the desert.
19½Ã 78:18 They tested God in their heart by demanding the food they craved.
19½Ã 78:19 They spoke against God, saying, "Can God spread a table in the wilderness?
19½Ã 78:20 Even though he struck the rock so that water gushed out and torrents overflowed, can he also give bread, or provide meat for his people?"
19½Ã 78:21 Therefore, when the LORD heard, he was full of rage; a fire was kindled against Jacob, his anger mounted against Israel,
19½Ã 78:22 because they had no faith in God, and did not trust his saving power.
19½Ã 78:23 Yet he commanded the skies above, and opened the doors of heaven;
19½Ã 78:24 he rained down on them manna to eat, and gave them the grain of heaven.
19½Ã 78:25 Mortals ate of the bread of angels; he sent them food in abundance.
19½Ã 78:26 He caused the east wind to blow in the heavens, and by his power he led out the south wind;
19½Ã 78:27 he rained flesh upon them like dust, winged birds like the sand of the seas;
19½Ã 78:28 he let them fall within their camp, all around their dwellings.
19½Ã 78:29 And they ate and were well filled, for he gave them what they craved.
19½Ã 78:30 But before they had satisfied their craving, while the food was still in their mouths,
19½Ã 78:31 the anger of God rose against them and he killed the strongest of them, and laid low the flower of Israel.
19½Ã 78:32 In spite of all this they still sinned; they did not believe in his wonders.
19½Ã 78:33 So he made their days vanish like a breath, and their years in terror.
19½Ã 78:34 When he killed them, they sought for him; they repented and sought God earnestly.
19½Ã 78:35 They remembered that God was their rock, the Most High God their redeemer.
19½Ã 78:36 But they flattered him with their mouths; they lied to him with their tongues.
19½Ã 78:37 Their heart was not steadfast toward him; they were not true to his covenant.
19½Ã 78:38 Yet he, being compassionate, forgave their iniquity, and did not destroy them; often he restrained his anger, and did not stir up all his wrath.
19½Ã 78:39 He remembered that they were but flesh, a wind that passes and does not come again.
19½Ã 78:40 How often they rebelled against him in the wilderness and grieved him in the desert!
19½Ã 78:41 They tested God again and again, and provoked the Holy One of Israel.
19½Ã 78:42 They did not keep in mind his power, or the day when he redeemed them from the foe;
19½Ã 78:43 when he displayed his signs in Egypt, and his miracles in the fields of Zoan.
19½Ã 78:44 He turned their rivers to blood, so that they could not drink of their streams.
19½Ã 78:45 He sent among them swarms of flies, which devoured them, and frogs, which destroyed them.
19½Ã 78:46 He gave their crops to the caterpillar, and the fruit of their labor to the locust.
19½Ã 78:47 He destroyed their vines with hail, and their sycamores with frost.
19½Ã 78:48 He gave over their cattle to the hail, and their flocks to thunderbolts.
19½Ã 78:49 He let loose on them his fierce anger, wrath, indignation, and distress, a company of destroying angels.
19½Ã 78:50 He made a path for his anger; he did not spare them from death, but gave their lives over to the plague.
19½Ã 78:51 He struck all the firstborn in Egypt, the first issue of their strength in the tents of Ham.
19½Ã 78:52 Then he led out his people like sheep, and guided them in the wilderness like a flock.
19½Ã 78:53 He led them in safety, so that they were not afraid; but the sea overwhelmed their enemies.
19½Ã 78:54 And he brought them to his holy hill, to the mountain that his right hand had won.
19½Ã 78:55 He drove out nations before them; he apportioned them for a possession and settled the tribes of Israel in their tents.
19½Ã 78:56 Yet they tested the Most High God, and rebelled against him. They did not observe his decrees,
19½Ã 78:57 but turned away and were faithless like their ancestors; they twisted like a treacherous bow.
19½Ã 78:58 For they provoked him to anger with their high places; they moved him to jealousy with their idols.
19½Ã 78:59 When God heard, he was full of wrath, and he utterly rejected Israel.
19½Ã 78:60 He abandoned his dwelling at Shiloh, the tent where he dwelt among mortals,
19½Ã 78:61 and delivered his power to captivity, his glory to the hand of the foe.
19½Ã 78:62 He gave his people to the sword, and vented his wrath on his heritage.
19½Ã 78:63 Fire devoured their young men, and their girls had no marriage song.
19½Ã 78:64 Their priests fell by the sword, and their widows made no lamentation.
19½Ã 78:65 Then the Lord awoke as from sleep, like a warrior shouting because of wine.
19½Ã 78:66 He put his adversaries to rout; he put them to everlasting disgrace.
19½Ã 78:67 He rejected the tent of Joseph, he did not choose the tribe of Ephraim;
19½Ã 78:68 but he chose the tribe of Judah, Mount Zion, which he loves.
19½Ã 78:69 He built his sanctuary like the high heavens, like the earth, which he has founded forever.
19½Ã 78:70 He chose his servant David, and took him from the sheepfolds;
19½Ã 78:71 from tending the nursing ewes he brought him to be the shepherd of his people Jacob, of Israel, his inheritance.
19½Ã 78:72 With upright heart he tended them, and guided them with skillful hand.
19½Ã 79:1 A Psalm of Asaph. O God, the nations have come into your inheritance; they have defiled your holy temple; they have laid Jerusalem in ruins.
19½Ã 79:2 They have given the bodies of your servants to the birds of the air for food, the flesh of your faithful to the wild animals of the earth.
19½Ã 79:3 They have poured out their blood like water all around Jerusalem, and there was no one to bury them.
19½Ã 79:4 We have become a taunt to our neighbors, mocked and derided by those around us.
19½Ã 79:5 How long, O LORD? Will you be angry forever? Will your jealous wrath burn like fire?
19½Ã 79:6 Pour out your anger on the nations that do not know you, and on the kingdoms that do not call on your name.
19½Ã 79:7 For they have devoured Jacob and laid waste his habitation.
19½Ã 79:8 Do not remember against us the iniquities of our ancestors; let your compassion come speedily to meet us, for we are brought very low.
19½Ã 79:9 Help us, O God of our salvation, for the glory of your name; deliver us, and forgive our sins, for your name's sake.
19½Ã 79:10 Why should the nations say, "Where is their God?" Let the avenging of the outpoured blood of your servants be known among the nations before our eyes.
19½Ã 79:11 Let the groans of the prisoners come before you; according to your great power preserve those doomed to die.
19½Ã 79:12 Return sevenfold into the bosom of our neighbors the taunts with which they taunted you, O Lord!
19½Ã 79:13 Then we your people, the flock of your pasture, will give thanks to you forever; from generation to generation we will recount your praise.
19½Ã 80:1 To the leader: on Lilies, a Covenant. Of Asaph. A Psalm. Give ear, O Shepherd of Israel, you who lead Joseph like a flock! You who are enthroned upon the cherubim, shine forth
19½Ã 80:2 before Ephraim and Benjamin and Manasseh. Stir up your might, and come to save us!
19½Ã 80:3 Restore us, O God; let your face shine, that we may be saved.
19½Ã 80:4 O LORD God of hosts, how long will you be angry with your people's prayers?
19½Ã 80:5 You have fed them with the bread of tears, and given them tears to drink in full measure.
19½Ã 80:6 You make us the scorn of our neighbors; our enemies laugh among themselves.
19½Ã 80:7 Restore us, O God of hosts; let your face shine, that we may be saved.
19½Ã 80:8 You brought a vine out of Egypt; you drove out the nations and planted it.
19½Ã 80:9 You cleared the ground for it; it took deep root and filled the land.
19½Ã 80:10 The mountains were covered with its shade, the mighty cedars with its branches;
19½Ã 80:11 it sent out its branches to the sea, and its shoots to the River.
19½Ã 80:12 Why then have you broken down its walls, so that all who pass along the way pluck its fruit?
19½Ã 80:13 The boar from the forest ravages it, and all that move in the field feed on it.
19½Ã 80:14 Turn again, O God of hosts; look down from heaven, and see; have regard for this vine,
19½Ã 80:15 the stock that your right hand planted.
19½Ã 80:16 They have burned it with fire, they have cut it down; may they perish at the rebuke of your countenance.
19½Ã 80:17 But let your hand be upon the one at your right hand, the one whom you made strong for yourself.
19½Ã 80:18 Then we will never turn back from you; give us life, and we will call on your name.
19½Ã 80:19 Restore us, O LORD God of hosts; let your face shine, that we may be saved.
19½Ã 81:1 To the leader: according to The Gittith. Of Asaph. Sing aloud to God our strength; shout for joy to the God of Jacob.
