20Àá 1:1 The proverbs of Solomon son of David, king of Israel:
20Àá 1:2 For learning about wisdom and instruction, for understanding words of insight,
20Àá 1:3 for gaining instruction in wise dealing, righteousness, justice, and equity;
20Àá 1:4 to teach shrewdness to the simple, knowledge and prudence to the young--
20Àá 1:5 Let the wise also hear and gain in learning, and the discerning acquire skill,
20Àá 1:6 to understand a proverb and a figure, the words of the wise and their riddles.
20Àá 1:7 The fear of the LORD is the beginning of knowledge; fools despise wisdom and instruction.
20Àá 1:8 Hear, my child, your father's instruction, and do not reject your mother's teaching;
20Àá 1:9 for they are a fair garland for your head, and pendants for your neck.
20Àá 1:10 My child, if sinners entice you, do not consent.
20Àá 1:11 If they say, "Come with us, let us lie in wait for blood; let us wantonly ambush the innocent;
20Àá 1:12 like Sheol let us swallow them alive and whole, like those who go down to the Pit.
20Àá 1:13 We shall find all kinds of costly things; we shall fill our houses with booty.
20Àá 1:14 Throw in your lot among us; we will all have one purse"--
20Àá 1:15 my child, do not walk in their way, keep your foot from their paths;
20Àá 1:16 for their feet run to evil, and they hurry to shed blood.
20Àá 1:17 For in vain is the net baited while the bird is looking on;
20Àá 1:18 yet they lie in wait--to kill themselves! and set an ambush--for their own lives!
20Àá 1:19 Such is the end of all who are greedy for gain; it takes away the life of its possessors.
20Àá 1:20 Wisdom cries out in the street; in the squares she raises her voice.
20Àá 1:21 At the busiest corner she cries out; at the entrance of the city gates she speaks:
20Àá 1:22 "How long, O simple ones, will you love being simple? How long will scoffers delight in their scoffing and fools hate knowledge?
20Àá 1:23 Give heed to my reproof; I will pour out my thoughts to you; I will make my words known to you.
20Àá 1:24 Because I have called and you refused, have stretched out my hand and no one heeded,
20Àá 1:25 and because you have ignored all my counsel and would have none of my reproof,
20Àá 1:26 I also will laugh at your calamity; I will mock when panic strikes you,
20Àá 1:27 when panic strikes you like a storm, and your calamity comes like a whirlwind, when distress and anguish come upon you.
20Àá 1:28 Then they will call upon me, but I will not answer; they will seek me diligently, but will not find me.
20Àá 1:29 Because they hated knowledge and did not choose the fear of the LORD,
20Àá 1:30 would have none of my counsel, and despised all my reproof,
20Àá 1:31 therefore they shall eat the fruit of their way and be sated with their own devices.
20Àá 1:32 For waywardness kills the simple, and the complacency of fools destroys them;
20Àá 1:33 but those who listen to me will be secure and will live at ease, without dread of disaster."
20Àá 2:1 My child, if you accept my words and treasure up my commandments within you,
20Àá 2:2 making your ear attentive to wisdom and inclining your heart to understanding;
20Àá 2:3 if you indeed cry out for insight, and raise your voice for understanding;
20Àá 2:4 if you seek it like silver, and search for it as for hidden treasures--
20Àá 2:5 then you will understand the fear of the LORD and find the knowledge of God.
20Àá 2:6 For the LORD gives wisdom; from his mouth come knowledge and understanding;
20Àá 2:7 he stores up sound wisdom for the upright; he is a shield to those who walk blamelessly,
20Àá 2:8 guarding the paths of justice and preserving the way of his faithful ones.
20Àá 2:9 Then you will understand righteousness and justice and equity, every good path;
20Àá 2:10 for wisdom will come into your heart, and knowledge will be pleasant to your soul;
20Àá 2:11 prudence will watch over you; and understanding will guard you.
20Àá 2:12 It will save you from the way of evil, from those who speak perversely,
20Àá 2:13 who forsake the paths of uprightness to walk in the ways of darkness,
20Àá 2:14 who rejoice in doing evil and delight in the perverseness of evil;
20Àá 2:15 those whose paths are crooked, and who are devious in their ways.
20Àá 2:16 You will be saved from the loose woman, from the adulteress with her smooth words,
20Àá 2:17 who forsakes the partner of her youth and forgets her sacred covenant;
20Àá 2:18 for her way leads down to death, and her paths to the shades;
20Àá 2:19 those who go to her never come back, nor do they regain the paths of life.
20Àá 2:20 Therefore walk in the way of the good, and keep to the paths of the just.
20Àá 2:21 For the upright will abide in the land, and the innocent will remain in it;
20Àá 2:22 but the wicked will be cut off from the land, and the treacherous will be rooted out of it.
20Àá 3:1 My child, do not forget my teaching, but let your heart keep my commandments;
20Àá 3:2 for length of days and years of life and abundant welfare they will give you.
20Àá 3:3 Do not let loyalty and faithfulness forsake you; bind them around your neck, write them on the tablet of your heart.
20Àá 3:4 So you will find favor and good repute in the sight of God and of people.
20Àá 3:5 Trust in the LORD with all your heart, and do not rely on your own insight.
20Àá 3:6 In all your ways acknowledge him, and he will make straight your paths.
20Àá 3:7 Do not be wise in your own eyes; fear the LORD, and turn away from evil.
20Àá 3:8 It will be a healing for your flesh and a refreshment for your body.
20Àá 3:9 Honor the LORD with your substance and with the first fruits of all your produce;
20Àá 3:10 then your barns will be filled with plenty, and your vats will be bursting with wine.
20Àá 3:11 My child, do not despise the LORD's discipline or be weary of his reproof,
20Àá 3:12 for the LORD reproves the one he loves, as a father the son in whom he delights.
20Àá 3:13 Happy are those who find wisdom, and those who get understanding,
20Àá 3:14 for her income is better than silver, and her revenue better than gold.
20Àá 3:15 She is more precious than jewels, and nothing you desire can compare with her.
20Àá 3:16 Long life is in her right hand; in her left hand are riches and honor.
20Àá 3:17 Her ways are ways of pleasantness, and all her paths are peace.
20Àá 3:18 She is a tree of life to those who lay hold of her; those who hold her fast are called happy.
20Àá 3:19 The LORD by wisdom founded the earth; by understanding he established the heavens;
20Àá 3:20 by his knowledge the deeps broke open, and the clouds drop down the dew.
20Àá 3:21 My child, do not let these escape from your sight: keep sound wisdom and prudence,
20Àá 3:22 and they will be life for your soul and adornment for your neck.
20Àá 3:23 Then you will walk on your way securely and your foot will not stumble.
20Àá 3:24 If you sit down, you will not be afraid; when you lie down, your sleep will be sweet.
20Àá 3:25 Do not be afraid of sudden panic, or of the storm that strikes the wicked;
20Àá 3:26 for the LORD will be your confidence and will keep your foot from being caught.
20Àá 3:27 Do not withhold good from those to whom it is due, when it is in your power to do it.
20Àá 3:28 Do not say to your neighbor, "Go, and come again, tomorrow I will give it"--when you have it with you.
20Àá 3:29 Do not plan harm against your neighbor who lives trustingly beside you.
20Àá 3:30 Do not quarrel with anyone without cause, when no harm has been done to you.
20Àá 3:31 Do not envy the violent and do not choose any of their ways;
20Àá 3:32 for the perverse are an abomination to the LORD, but the upright are in his confidence.
20Àá 3:33 The LORD's curse is on the house of the wicked, but he blesses the abode of the righteous.
20Àá 3:34 Toward the scorners he is scornful, but to the humble he shows favor.
20Àá 3:35 The wise will inherit honor, but stubborn fools, disgrace.
20Àá 4:1 Listen, children, to a father's instruction, and be attentive, that you may gain insight;
20Àá 4:2 for I give you good precepts: do not forsake my teaching.
20Àá 4:3 When I was a son with my father, tender, and my mother's favorite,
20Àá 4:4 he taught me, and said to me, "Let your heart hold fast my words; keep my commandments, and live.
20Àá 4:5 Get wisdom; get insight: do not forget, nor turn away from the words of my mouth.
20Àá 4:6 Do not forsake her, and she will keep you; love her, and she will guard you.
20Àá 4:7 The beginning of wisdom is this: Get wisdom, and whatever else you get, get insight.
20Àá 4:8 Prize her highly, and she will exalt you; she will honor you if you embrace her.
20Àá 4:9 She will place on your head a fair garland; she will bestow on you a beautiful crown."
20Àá 4:10 Hear, my child, and accept my words, that the years of your life may be many.
20Àá 4:11 I have taught you the way of wisdom; I have led you in the paths of uprightness.
20Àá 4:12 When you walk, your step will not be hampered; and if you run, you will not stumble.
20Àá 4:13 Keep hold of instruction; do not let go; guard her, for she is your life.
20Àá 4:14 Do not enter the path of the wicked, and do not walk in the way of evildoers.
20Àá 4:15 Avoid it; do not go on it; turn away from it and pass on.
20Àá 4:16 For they cannot sleep unless they have done wrong; they are robbed of sleep unless they have made someone stumble.
20Àá 4:17 For they eat the bread of wickedness and drink the wine of violence.
20Àá 4:18 But the path of the righteous is like the light of dawn, which shines brighter and brighter until full day.
20Àá 4:19 The way of the wicked is like deep darkness; they do not know what they stumble over.
20Àá 4:20 My child, be attentive to my words; incline your ear to my sayings.
20Àá 4:21 Do not let them escape from your sight; keep them within your heart.
20Àá 4:22 For they are life to those who find them, and healing to all their flesh.
20Àá 4:23 Keep your heart with all vigilance, for from it flow the springs of life.
20Àá 4:24 Put away from you crooked speech, and put devious talk far from you.
20Àá 4:25 Let your eyes look directly forward, and your gaze be straight before you.
20Àá 4:26 Keep straight the path of your feet, and all your ways will be sure.
20Àá 4:27 Do not swerve to the right or to the left; turn your foot away from evil.
20Àá 5:1 My child, be attentive to my wisdom; incline your ear to my understanding,
20Àá 5:2 so that you may hold on to prudence, and your lips may guard knowledge.
20Àá 5:3 For the lips of a loose woman drip honey, and her speech is smoother than oil;
20Àá 5:4 but in the end she is bitter as wormwood, sharp as a two-edged sword.
20Àá 5:5 Her feet go down to death; her steps follow the path to Sheol.
20Àá 5:6 She does not keep straight to the path of life; her ways wander, and she does not know it.
20Àá 5:7 And now, my child, listen to me, and do not depart from the words of my mouth.
20Àá 5:8 Keep your way far from her, and do not go near the door of her house;
20Àá 5:9 or you will give your honor to others, and your years to the merciless,
20Àá 5:10 and strangers will take their fill of your wealth, and your labors will go to the house of an alien;
20Àá 5:11 and at the end of your life you will groan, when your flesh and body are consumed,
20Àá 5:12 and you say, "Oh, how I hated discipline, and my heart despised reproof!
20Àá 5:13 I did not listen to the voice of my teachers or incline my ear to my instructors.
20Àá 5:14 Now I am at the point of utter ruin in the public assembly."
20Àá 5:15 Drink water from your own cistern, flowing water from your own well.
20Àá 5:16 Should your springs be scattered abroad, streams of water in the streets?
20Àá 5:17 Let them be for yourself alone, and not for sharing with strangers.
20Àá 5:18 Let your fountain be blessed, and rejoice in the wife of your youth,
20Àá 5:19 a lovely deer, a graceful doe. May her breasts satisfy you at all times; may you be intoxicated always by her love.
20Àá 5:20 Why should you be intoxicated, my son, by another woman and embrace the bosom of an adulteress?
20Àá 5:21 For human ways are under the eyes of the LORD, and he examines all their paths.
20Àá 5:22 The iniquities of the wicked ensnare them, and they are caught in the toils of their sin.
20Àá 5:23 They die for lack of discipline, and because of their great folly they are lost.
20Àá 6:1 My child, if you have given your pledge to your neighbor, if you have bound yourself to another,
20Àá 6:2 you are snared by the utterance of your lips, caught by the words of your mouth.
20Àá 6:3 So do this, my child, and save yourself, for you have come into your neighbor's power: go, hurry, and plead with your neighbor.
20Àá 6:4 Give your eyes no sleep and your eyelids no slumber;
20Àá 6:5 save yourself like a gazelle from the hunter, like a bird from the hand of the fowler.
20Àá 6:6 Go to the ant, you lazybones; consider its ways, and be wise.
20Àá 6:7 Without having any chief or officer or ruler,
20Àá 6:8 it prepares its food in summer, and gathers its sustenance in harvest.
20Àá 6:9 How long will you lie there, O lazybones? When will you rise from your sleep?
20Àá 6:10 A little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the hands to rest,
20Àá 6:11 and poverty will come upon you like a robber, and want, like an armed warrior.
20Àá 6:12 A scoundrel and a villain goes around with crooked speech,
20Àá 6:13 winking the eyes, shuffling the feet, pointing the fingers,
20Àá 6:14 with perverted mind devising evil, continually sowing discord;
20Àá 6:15 on such a one calamity will descend suddenly; in a moment, damage beyond repair.
20Àá 6:16 There are six things that the LORD hates, seven that are an abomination to him:
20Àá 6:17 haughty eyes, a lying tongue, and hands that shed innocent blood,
20Àá 6:18 a heart that devises wicked plans, feet that hurry to run to evil,
20Àá 6:19 a lying witness who testifies falsely, and one who sows discord in a family.
20Àá 6:20 My child, keep your father's commandment, and do not forsake your mother's teaching.
20Àá 6:21 Bind them upon your heart always; tie them around your neck.
20Àá 6:22 When you walk, they will lead you; when you lie down, they will watch over you; and when you awake, they will talk with you.
20Àá 6:23 For the commandment is a lamp and the teaching a light, and the reproofs of discipline are the way of life,
20Àá 6:24 to preserve you from the wife of another, from the smooth tongue of the adulteress.
20Àá 6:25 Do not desire her beauty in your heart, and do not let her capture you with her eyelashes;
20Àá 6:26 for a prostitute's fee is only a loaf of bread, but the wife of another stalks a man's very life.
20Àá 6:27 Can fire be carried in the bosom without burning one's clothes?
20Àá 6:28 Or can one walk on hot coals without scorching the feet?
20Àá 6:29 So is he who sleeps with his neighbor's wife; no one who touches her will go unpunished.
20Àá 6:30 Thieves are not despised who steal only to satisfy their appetite when they are hungry.
20Àá 6:31 Yet if they are caught, they will pay sevenfold; they will forfeit all the goods of their house.
20Àá 6:32 But he who commits adultery has no sense; he who does it destroys himself.
20Àá 6:33 He will get wounds and dishonor, and his disgrace will not be wiped away.
20Àá 6:34 For jealousy arouses a husband's fury, and he shows no restraint when he takes revenge.
20Àá 6:35 He will accept no compensation, and refuses a bribe no matter how great.
20Àá 7:1 My child, keep my words and store up my commandments with you;
20Àá 7:2 keep my commandments and live, keep my teachings as the apple of your eye;
20Àá 7:3 bind them on your fingers, write them on the tablet of your heart.
20Àá 7:4 Say to wisdom, "You are my sister," and call insight your intimate friend,
20Àá 7:5 that they may keep you from the loose woman, from the adulteress with her smooth words.
20Àá 7:6 For at the window of my house I looked out through my lattice,
20Àá 7:7 and I saw among the simple ones, I observed among the youths, a young man without sense,
20Àá 7:8 passing along the street near her corner, taking the road to her house
20Àá 7:9 in the twilight, in the evening, at the time of night and darkness.
20Àá 7:10 Then a woman comes toward him, decked out like a prostitute, wily of heart.
20Àá 7:11 She is loud and wayward; her feet do not stay at home;
20Àá 7:12 now in the street, now in the squares, and at every corner she lies in wait.
20Àá 7:13 She seizes him and kisses him, and with impudent face she says to him:
20Àá 7:14 "I had to offer sacrifices, and today I have paid my vows;
20Àá 7:15 so now I have come out to meet you, to seek you eagerly, and I have found you!
20Àá 7:16 I have decked my couch with coverings, colored spreads of Egyptian linen;
20Àá 7:17 I have perfumed my bed with myrrh, aloes, and cinnamon.
20Àá 7:18 Come, let us take our fill of love until morning; let us delight ourselves with love.
20Àá 7:19 For my husband is not at home; he has gone on a long journey.
20Àá 7:20 He took a bag of money with him; he will not come home until full moon."
20Àá 7:21 With much seductive speech she persuades him; with her smooth talk she compels him.
20Àá 7:22 Right away he follows her, and goes like an ox to the slaughter, or bounds like a stag toward the trap
20Àá 7:23 until an arrow pierces its entrails. He is like a bird rushing into a snare, not knowing that it will cost him his life.
20Àá 7:24 And now, my children, listen to me, and be attentive to the words of my mouth.
20Àá 7:25 Do not let your hearts turn aside to her ways; do not stray into her paths.
20Àá 7:26 for many are those she has laid low, and numerous are her victims.
20Àá 7:27 Her house is the way to Sheol, going down to the chambers of death.
20Àá 8:1 Does not wisdom call, and does not understanding raise her voice?
20Àá 8:2 On the heights, beside the way, at the crossroads she takes her stand;
20Àá 8:3 beside the gates in front of the town, at the entrance of the portals she cries out:
20Àá 8:4 "To you, O people, I call, and my cry is to all that live.
20Àá 8:5 O simple ones, learn prudence; acquire intelligence, you who lack it.
20Àá 8:6 Hear, for I will speak noble things, and from my lips will come what is right;
20Àá 8:7 for my mouth will utter truth; wickedness is an abomination to my lips.
20Àá 8:8 All the words of my mouth are righteous; there is nothing twisted or crooked in them.
20Àá 8:9 They are all straight to one who understands and right to those who find knowledge.
20Àá 8:10 Take my instruction instead of silver, and knowledge rather than choice gold;
20Àá 8:11 for wisdom is better than jewels, and all that you may desire cannot compare with her.
20Àá 8:12 I, wisdom, live with prudence, and I attain knowledge and discretion.
20Àá 8:13 The fear of the LORD is hatred of evil. Pride and arrogance and the way of evil and perverted speech I hate.
20Àá 8:14 I have good advice and sound wisdom; I have insight, I have strength.
20Àá 8:15 By me kings reign, and rulers decree what is just;
20Àá 8:16 by me rulers rule, and nobles, all who govern rightly.
20Àá 8:17 I love those who love me, and those who seek me diligently find me.
20Àá 8:18 Riches and honor are with me, enduring wealth and prosperity.
20Àá 8:19 My fruit is better than gold, even fine gold, and my yield than choice silver.
20Àá 8:20 I walk in the way of righteousness, along the paths of justice,
20Àá 8:21 endowing with wealth those who love me, and filling their treasuries.
20Àá 8:22 The LORD created me at the beginning of his work, the first of his acts of long ago.
20Àá 8:23 Ages ago I was set up, at the first, before the beginning of the earth.
20Àá 8:24 When there were no depths I was brought forth, when there were no springs abounding with water.
20Àá 8:25 Before the mountains had been shaped, before the hills, I was brought forth--
20Àá 8:26 when he had not yet made earth and fields, or the world's first bits of soil.
20Àá 8:27 When he established the heavens, I was there, when he drew a circle on the face of the deep,
20Àá 8:28 when he made firm the skies above, when he established the fountains of the deep,
20Àá 8:29 when he assigned to the sea its limit, so that the waters might not transgress his command, when he marked out the foundations of the earth,
20Àá 8:30 then I was beside him, like a master worker; and I was daily his delight, rejoicing before him always,
20Àá 8:31 rejoicing in his inhabited world and delighting in the human race.
20Àá 8:32 And now, my children, listen to me: happy are those who keep my ways.
20Àá 8:33 Hear instruction and be wise, and do not neglect it.
20Àá 8:34 Happy is the one who listens to me, watching daily at my gates, waiting beside my doors.
20Àá 8:35 For whoever finds me finds life and obtains favor from the LORD;
20Àá 8:36 but those who miss me injure themselves; all who hate me love death."
20Àá 9:1 Wisdom has built her house, she has hewn her seven pillars.
20Àá 9:2 She has slaughtered her animals, she has mixed her wine, she has also set her table.
20Àá 9:3 She has sent out her servant girls, she calls from the highest places in the town,
20Àá 9:4 "You that are simple, turn in here!" To those without sense she says,
20Àá 9:5 "Come, eat of my bread and drink of the wine I have mixed.
20Àá 9:6 Lay aside immaturity, and live, and walk in the way of insight."
20Àá 9:7 Whoever corrects a scoffer wins abuse; whoever rebukes the wicked gets hurt.
20Àá 9:8 A scoffer who is rebuked will only hate you; the wise, when rebuked, will love you.
20Àá 9:9 Give instruction to the wise, and they will become wiser still; teach the righteous and they will gain in learning.
20Àá 9:10 The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom, and the knowledge of the Holy One is insight.
20Àá 9:11 For by me your days will be multiplied, and years will be added to your life.
20Àá 9:12 If you are wise, you are wise for yourself; if you scoff, you alone will bear it.
20Àá 9:13 The foolish woman is loud; she is ignorant and knows nothing.
20Àá 9:14 She sits at the door of her house, on a seat at the high places of the town,
20Àá 9:15 calling to those who pass by, who are going straight on their way,
20Àá 9:16 "You who are simple, turn in here!" And to those without sense she says,
20Àá 9:17 "Stolen water is sweet, and bread eaten in secret is pleasant."
20Àá 9:18 But they do not know that the dead are there, that her guests are in the depths of Sheol.
20Àá 10:1 The proverbs of Solomon. A wise child makes a glad father, but a foolish child is a mother's grief.
20Àá 10:2 Treasures gained by wickedness do not profit, but righteousness delivers from death.
20Àá 10:3 The LORD does not let the righteous go hungry, but he thwarts the craving of the wicked.
20Àá 10:4 A slack hand causes poverty, but the hand of the diligent makes rich.
20Àá 10:5 A child who gathers in summer is prudent, but a child who sleeps in harvest brings shame.
20Àá 10:6 Blessings are on the head of the righteous, but the mouth of the wicked conceals violence.
20Àá 10:7 The memory of the righteous is a blessing, but the name of the wicked will rot.
20Àá 10:8 The wise of heart will heed commandments, but a babbling fool will come to ruin.
20Àá 10:9 Whoever walks in integrity walks securely, but whoever follows perverse ways will be found out.
20Àá 10:10 Whoever winks the eye causes trouble, but the one who rebukes boldly makes peace.
20Àá 10:11 The mouth of the righteous is a fountain of life, but the mouth of the wicked conceals violence.
20Àá 10:12 Hatred stirs up strife, but love covers all offenses.
20Àá 10:13 On the lips of one who has understanding wisdom is found, but a rod is for the back of one who lacks sense.
20Àá 10:14 The wise lay up knowledge, but the babbling of a fool brings ruin near.
20Àá 10:15 The wealth of the rich is their fortress; the poverty of the poor is their ruin.
20Àá 10:16 The wage of the righteous leads to life, the gain of the wicked to sin.
20Àá 10:17 Whoever heeds instruction is on the path to life, but one who rejects a rebuke goes astray.
20Àá 10:18 Lying lips conceal hatred, and whoever utters slander is a fool.
20Àá 10:19 When words are many, transgression is not lacking, but the prudent are restrained in speech.
20Àá 10:20 The tongue of the righteous is choice silver; the mind of the wicked is of little worth.
20Àá 10:21 The lips of the righteous feed many, but fools die for lack of sense.
20Àá 10:22 The blessing of the LORD makes rich, and he adds no sorrow with it.
20Àá 10:23 Doing wrong is like sport to a fool, but wise conduct is pleasure to a person of understanding.
20Àá 10:24 What the wicked dread will come upon them, but the desire of the righteous will be granted.
20Àá 10:25 When the tempest passes, the wicked are no more, but the righteous are established forever.
20Àá 10:26 Like vinegar to the teeth, and smoke to the eyes, so are the lazy to their employers.
20Àá 10:27 The fear of the LORD prolongs life, but the years of the wicked will be short.
20Àá 10:28 The hope of the righteous ends in gladness, but the expectation of the wicked comes to nothing.
20Àá 10:29 The way of the LORD is a stronghold for the upright, but destruction for evildoers.
20Àá 10:30 The righteous will never be removed, but the wicked will not remain in the land.
20Àá 10:31 The mouth of the righteous brings forth wisdom, but the perverse tongue will be cut off.
20Àá 10:32 The lips of the righteous know what is acceptable, but the mouth of the wicked what is perverse.
20Àá 11:1 A false balance is an abomination to the LORD, but an accurate weight is his delight.
20Àá 11:2 When pride comes, then comes disgrace; but wisdom is with the humble.
20Àá 11:3 The integrity of the upright guides them, but the crookedness of the treacherous destroys them.
20Àá 11:4 Riches do not profit in the day of wrath, but righteousness delivers from death.
20Àá 11:5 The righteousness of the blameless keeps their ways straight, but the wicked fall by their own wickedness.
20Àá 11:6 The righteousness of the upright saves them, but the treacherous are taken captive by their schemes.
20Àá 11:7 When the wicked die, their hope perishes, and the expectation of the godless comes to nothing.
20Àá 11:8 The righteous are delivered from trouble, and the wicked get into it instead.
20Àá 11:9 With their mouths the godless would destroy their neighbors, but by knowledge the righteous are delivered.
20Àá 11:10 When it goes well with the righteous, the city rejoices; and when the wicked perish, there is jubilation.
20Àá 11:11 By the blessing of the upright a city is exalted, but it is overthrown by the mouth of the wicked.
20Àá 11:12 Whoever belittles another lacks sense, but an intelligent person remains silent.
20Àá 11:13 A gossip goes about telling secrets, but one who is trustworthy in spirit keeps a confidence.
20Àá 11:14 Where there is no guidance, a nation falls, but in an abundance of counselors there is safety.
20Àá 11:15 To guarantee loans for a stranger brings trouble, but there is safety in refusing to do so.
20Àá 11:16 A gracious woman gets honor, but she who hates virtue is covered with shame. The timid become destitute, but the aggressive gain riches.
20Àá 11:17 Those who are kind reward themselves, but the cruel do themselves harm.
20Àá 11:18 The wicked earn no real gain, but those who sow righteousness get a true reward.
20Àá 11:19 Whoever is steadfast in righteousness will live, but whoever pursues evil will die.
20Àá 11:20 Crooked minds are an abomination to the LORD, but those of blameless ways are his delight.
20Àá 11:21 Be assured, the wicked will not go unpunished, but those who are righteous will escape.
20Àá 11:22 Like a gold ring in a pig's snout is a beautiful woman without good sense.
20Àá 11:23 The desire of the righteous ends only in good; the expectation of the wicked in wrath.
20Àá 11:24 Some give freely, yet grow all the richer; Others withhold what is due, and only suffer want.
20Àá 11:25 A generous person will be enriched, and one who gives water will get water.
20Àá 11:26 The people curse those who hold back grain, but a blessing is on the head of those who sell it.
20Àá 11:27 Whoever diligently seeks good seeks favor, but evil comes to the one who searches for it.
20Àá 11:28 Those who trust in their riches will wither, but the righteous will flourish like green leaves.
20Àá 11:29 Those who trouble their households will inherit wind, and the fool will be servant to the wise.
20Àá 11:30 The fruit of the righteous is a tree of life, but violence takes lives away.
20Àá 11:31 If the righteous are repaid on earth, how much more the wicked and the sinner!
20Àá 12:1 Whoever loves discipline loves knowledge, but those who hate to be rebuked are stupid.
20Àá 12:2 The good obtain favor from the LORD, but those who devise evil he condemns.
20Àá 12:3 No one finds security by wickedness, but the root of the righteous will never be moved.
20Àá 12:4 A good wife is the crown of her husband, but she who brings shame is like rottenness in his bones.
20Àá 12:5 The thoughts of the righteous are just; the advice of the wicked is treacherous.
20Àá 12:6 The words of the wicked are a deadly ambush, but the speech of the upright delivers them.
20Àá 12:7 The wicked are overthrown and are no more, but the house of the righteous will stand.
20Àá 12:8 One is commended for good sense, but a perverse mind is despised.
20Àá 12:9 Better to be despised and have a servant, than to be self-important and lack food.
20Àá 12:10 The righteous know the needs of their animals, but the mercy of the wicked is cruel.
20Àá 12:11 Those who till their land will have plenty of food, but those who follow worthless pursuits have no sense.
20Àá 12:12 The wicked covet the proceeds of wickedness, but the root of the righteous bears fruit.
20Àá 12:13 The evil are ensnared by the transgression of their lips, but the righteous escape from trouble.
20Àá 12:14 From the fruit of the mouth one is filled with good things, and manual labor has its reward.
20Àá 12:15 Fools think their own way is right, but the wise listen to advice.
20Àá 12:16 Fools show their anger at once, but the prudent ignore an insult.
20Àá 12:17 Whoever speaks the truth gives honest evidence, but a false witness speaks deceitfully.
20Àá 12:18 Rash words are like sword thrusts, but the tongue of the wise brings healing.
20Àá 12:19 Truthful lips endure forever, but a lying tongue lasts only a moment.
20Àá 12:20 Deceit is in the mind of those who plan evil, but those who counsel peace have joy.
20Àá 12:21 No harm happens to the righteous, but the wicked are filled with trouble.
20Àá 12:22 Lying lips are an abomination to the LORD, but those who act faithfully are his delight.
20Àá 12:23 One who is clever conceals knowledge, but the mind of a fool broadcasts folly.
20Àá 12:24 The hand of the diligent will rule, while the lazy will be put to forced labor.
20Àá 12:25 Anxiety weighs down the human heart, but a good word cheers it up.
20Àá 12:26 The righteous gives good advice to friends, but the way of the wicked leads astray.
20Àá 12:27 The lazy do not roast their game, but the diligent obtain precious wealth.
20Àá 12:28 In the path of righteousness there is life, in walking its path there is no death.
20Àá 13:1 A wise child loves discipline, but a scoffer does not listen to rebuke.
20Àá 13:2 From the fruit of their words good persons eat good things, but the desire of the treacherous is for wrongdoing.
20Àá 13:3 Those who guard their mouths preserve their lives; those who open wide their lips come to ruin.
20Àá 13:4 The appetite of the lazy craves, and gets nothing, while the appetite of the diligent is richly supplied.
20Àá 13:5 The righteous hate falsehood, but the wicked act shamefully and disgracefully.
20Àá 13:6 Righteousness guards one whose way is upright, but sin overthrows the wicked.
20Àá 13:7 Some pretend to be rich, yet have nothing; others pretend to be poor, yet have great wealth.
20Àá 13:8 Wealth is a ransom for a person's life, but the poor get no threats.
20Àá 13:9 The light of the righteous rejoices, but the lamp of the wicked goes out.
20Àá 13:10 By insolence the heedless make strife, but wisdom is with those who take advice.
20Àá 13:11 Wealth hastily gotten will dwindle, but those who gather little by little will increase it.
20Àá 13:12 Hope deferred makes the heart sick, but a desire fulfilled is a tree of life.
20Àá 13:13 Those who despise the word bring destruction on themselves, but those who respect the commandment will be rewarded.
20Àá 13:14 The teaching of the wise is a fountain of life, so that one may avoid the snares of death.
20Àá 13:15 Good sense wins favor, but the way of the faithless is their ruin.
20Àá 13:16 The clever do all things intelligently, but the fool displays folly.
20Àá 13:17 A bad messenger brings trouble, but a faithful envoy, healing.
20Àá 13:18 Poverty and disgrace are for the one who ignores instruction, but one who heeds reproof is honored.
20Àá 13:19 A desire realized is sweet to the soul, but to turn away from evil is an abomination to fools.
20Àá 13:20 Whoever walks with the wise becomes wise, but the companion of fools suffers harm.
20Àá 13:21 Misfortune pursues sinners, but prosperity rewards the righteous.
20Àá 13:22 The good leave an inheritance to their children's children, but the sinner's wealth is laid up for the righteous.
20Àá 13:23 The field of the poor may yield much food, but it is swept away through injustice.
20Àá 13:24 Those who spare the rod hate their children, but those who love them are diligent to discipline them.
20Àá 13:25 The righteous have enough to satisfy their appetite, but the belly of the wicked is empty.
20Àá 14:1 The wise woman builds her house, but the foolish tears it down with her own hands.
20Àá 14:2 Those who walk uprightly fear the LORD, but one who is devious in conduct despises him.
20Àá 14:3 The talk of fools is a rod for their backs, but the lips of the wise preserve them.
20Àá 14:4 Where there are no oxen, there is no grain; abundant crops come by the strength of the ox.
20Àá 14:5 A faithful witness does not lie, but a false witness breathes out lies.
20Àá 14:6 A scoffer seeks wisdom in vain, but knowledge is easy for one who understands.
20Àá 14:7 Leave the presence of a fool, for there you do not find words of knowledge.
20Àá 14:8 It is the wisdom of the clever to understand where they go, but the folly of fools misleads.
20Àá 14:9 Fools mock at the guilt offering, but the upright enjoy God's favor.
20Àá 14:10 The heart knows its own bitterness, and no stranger shares its joy.
20Àá 14:11 The house of the wicked is destroyed, but the tent of the upright flourishes.
20Àá 14:12 There is a way that seems right to a person, but its end is the way to death.
20Àá 14:13 Even in laughter the heart is sad, and the end of joy is grief.
20Àá 14:14 The perverse get what their ways deserve, and the good, what their deeds deserve.
20Àá 14:15 The simple believe everything, but the clever consider their steps.
20Àá 14:16 The wise are cautious and turn away from evil, but the fool throws off restraint and is careless.
20Àá 14:17 One who is quick-tempered acts foolishly, and the schemer is hated.
20Àá 14:18 The simple are adorned with folly, but the clever are crowned with knowledge.
20Àá 14:19 The evil bow down before the good, the wicked at the gates of the righteous.
20Àá 14:20 The poor are disliked even by their neighbors, but the rich have many friends.
20Àá 14:21 Those who despise their neighbors are sinners, but happy are those who are kind to the poor.
20Àá 14:22 Do they not err that plan evil? Those who plan good find loyalty and faithfulness.
20Àá 14:23 In all toil there is profit, but mere talk leads only to poverty.
20Àá 14:24 The crown of the wise is their wisdom, but folly is the garland of fools.
20Àá 14:25 A truthful witness saves lives, but one who utters lies is a betrayer.
20Àá 14:26 In the fear of the LORD one has strong confidence, and one's children will have a refuge.
20Àá 14:27 The fear of the LORD is a fountain of life, so that one may avoid the snares of death.
20Àá 14:28 The glory of a king is a multitude of people; without people a prince is ruined.
20Àá 14:29 Whoever is slow to anger has great understanding, but one who has a hasty temper exalts folly.
20Àá 14:30 A tranquil mind gives life to the flesh, but passion makes the bones rot.
20Àá 14:31 Those who oppress the poor insult their Maker, but those who are kind to the needy honor him.
20Àá 14:32 The wicked are overthrown by their evil-doing, but the righteous find a refuge in their integrity.
20Àá 14:33 Wisdom is at home in the mind of one who has understanding, but it is not known in the heart of fools.
20Àá 14:34 Righteousness exalts a nation, but sin is a reproach to any people.
20Àá 14:35 A servant who deals wisely has the king's favor, but his wrath falls on one who acts shamefully.
20Àá 15:1 A soft answer turns away wrath, but a harsh word stirs up anger.
20Àá 15:2 The tongue of the wise dispenses knowledge, but the mouths of fools pour out folly.
20Àá 15:3 The eyes of the LORD are in every place, keeping watch on the evil and the good.
20Àá 15:4 A gentle tongue is a tree of life, but perverseness in it breaks the spirit.
20Àá 15:5 A fool despises a parent's instruction, but the one who heeds admonition is prudent.
20Àá 15:6 In the house of the righteous there is much treasure, but trouble befalls the income of the wicked.
20Àá 15:7 The lips of the wise spread knowledge; not so the minds of fools.
20Àá 15:8 The sacrifice of the wicked is an abomination to the LORD, but the prayer of the upright is his delight.
20Àá 15:9 The way of the wicked is an abomination to the LORD, but he loves the one who pursues righteousness.
20Àá 15:10 There is severe discipline for one who forsakes the way, but one who hates a rebuke will die.
20Àá 15:11 Sheol and Abaddon lie open before the LORD, how much more human hearts!
20Àá 15:12 Scoffers do not like to be rebuked; they will not go to the wise.
20Àá 15:13 A glad heart makes a cheerful countenance, but by sorrow of heart the spirit is broken.
20Àá 15:14 The mind of one who has understanding seeks knowledge, but the mouths of fools feed on folly.
20Àá 15:15 All the days of the poor are hard, but a cheerful heart has a continual feast.
20Àá 15:16 Better is a little with the fear of the LORD than great treasure and trouble with it.
20Àá 15:17 Better is a dinner of vegetables where love is than a fatted ox and hatred with it.
20Àá 15:18 Those who are hot-tempered stir up strife, but those who are slow to anger calm contention.
20Àá 15:19 The way of the lazy is overgrown with thorns, but the path of the upright is a level highway.
20Àá 15:20 A wise child makes a glad father, but the foolish despise their mothers.
20Àá 15:21 Folly is a joy to one who has no sense, but a person of understanding walks straight ahead.
20Àá 15:22 Without counsel, plans go wrong, but with many advisers they succeed.
20Àá 15:23 To make an apt answer is a joy to anyone, and a word in season, how good it is!
20Àá 15:24 For the wise the path of life leads upward, in order to avoid Sheol below.
20Àá 15:25 The LORD tears down the house of the proud, but maintains the widow's boundaries.
20Àá 15:26 Evil plans are an abomination to the LORD, but gracious words are pure.
20Àá 15:27 Those who are greedy for unjust gain make trouble for their households, but those who hate bribes will live.
20Àá 15:28 The mind of the righteous ponders how to answer, but the mouth of the wicked pours out evil.
20Àá 15:29 The LORD is far from the wicked, but he hears the prayer of the righteous.
20Àá 15:30 The light of the eyes rejoices the heart, and good news refreshes the body.
20Àá 15:31 The ear that heeds wholesome admonition will lodge among the wise.
20Àá 15:32 Those who ignore instruction despise themselves, but those who heed admonition gain understanding.
20Àá 15:33 The fear of the LORD is instruction in wisdom, and humility goes before honor.
20Àá 16:1 The plans of the mind belong to mortals, but the answer of the tongue is from the LORD.
20Àá 16:2 All one's ways may be pure in one's own eyes, but the LORD weighs the spirit.
20Àá 16:3 Commit your work to the LORD, and your plans will be established.
20Àá 16:4 The LORD has made everything for its purpose, even the wicked for the day of trouble.
20Àá 16:5 All those who are arrogant are an abomination to the LORD; be assured, they will not go unpunished.
20Àá 16:6 By loyalty and faithfulness iniquity is atoned for, and by the fear of the LORD one avoids evil.
20Àá 16:7 When the ways of people please the LORD, he causes even their enemies to be at peace with them.
20Àá 16:8 Better is a little with righteousness than large income with injustice.
20Àá 16:9 The human mind plans the way, but the LORD directs the steps.
20Àá 16:10 Inspired decisions are on the lips of a king; his mouth does not sin in judgment.
20Àá 16:11 Honest balances and scales are the LORD's; all the weights in the bag are his work.
20Àá 16:12 It is an abomination to kings to do evil, for the throne is established by righteousness.
20Àá 16:13 Righteous lips are the delight of a king, and he loves those who speak what is right.
20Àá 16:14 A king's wrath is a messenger of death, and whoever is wise will appease it.
20Àá 16:15 In the light of a king's face there is life, and his favor is like the clouds that bring the spring rain.
20Àá 16:16 How much better to get wisdom than gold! To get understanding is to be chosen rather than silver.
20Àá 16:17 The highway of the upright avoids evil; those who guard their way preserve their lives.
20Àá 16:18 Pride goes before destruction, and a haughty spirit before a fall.
20Àá 16:19 It is better to be of a lowly spirit among the poor than to divide the spoil with the proud.
20Àá 16:20 Those who are attentive to a matter will prosper, and happy are those who trust in the LORD.
20Àá 16:21 The wise of heart is called perceptive, and pleasant speech increases persuasiveness.
20Àá 16:22 Wisdom is a fountain of life to one who has it, but folly is the punishment of fools.
20Àá 16:23 The mind of the wise makes their speech judicious, and adds persuasiveness to their lips.
20Àá 16:24 Pleasant words are like a honeycomb, sweetness to the soul and health to the body.
20Àá 16:25 Sometimes there is a way that seems to be right, but in the end it is the way to death.
20Àá 16:26 The appetite of workers works for them; their hunger urges them on.
20Àá 16:27 Scoundrels concoct evil, and their speech is like a scorching fire.
20Àá 16:28 A perverse person spreads strife, and a whisperer separates close friends.
20Àá 16:29 The violent entice their neighbors, and lead them in a way that is not good.
20Àá 16:30 One who winks the eyes plans perverse things; one who compresses the lips brings evil to pass.
20Àá 16:31 Gray hair is a crown of glory; it is gained in a righteous life.
20Àá 16:32 One who is slow to anger is better than the mighty, and one whose temper is controlled than one who captures a city.
20Àá 16:33 The lot is cast into the lap, but the decision is the LORD's alone.
20Àá 17:1 Better is a dry morsel with quiet than a house full of feasting with strife.
20Àá 17:2 A slave who deals wisely will rule over a child who acts shamefully, and will share the inheritance as one of the family.
20Àá 17:3 The crucible is for silver, and the furnace is for gold, but the LORD tests the heart.
20Àá 17:4 An evildoer listens to wicked lips; and a liar gives heed to a mischievous tongue.
20Àá 17:5 Those who mock the poor insult their Maker; those who are glad at calamity will not go unpunished.
20Àá 17:6 Grandchildren are the crown of the aged, and the glory of children is their parents.
20Àá 17:7 Fine speech is not becoming to a fool; still less is false speech to a ruler.
20Àá 17:8 A bribe is like a magic stone in the eyes of those who give it; wherever they turn they prosper.
20Àá 17:9 One who forgives an affront fosters friendship, but one who dwells on disputes will alienate a friend.
20Àá 17:10 A rebuke strikes deeper into a discerning person than a hundred blows into a fool.
20Àá 17:11 Evil people seek only rebellion, but a cruel messenger will be sent against them.
20Àá 17:12 Better to meet a she-bear robbed of its cubs than to confront a fool immersed in folly.
20Àá 17:13 Evil will not depart from the house of one who returns evil for good.
20Àá 17:14 The beginning of strife is like letting out water; so stop before the quarrel breaks out.
20Àá 17:15 One who justifies the wicked and one who condemns the righteous are both alike an abomination to the LORD.
20Àá 17:16 Why should fools have a price in hand to buy wisdom, when they have no mind to learn?
20Àá 17:17 A friend loves at all times, and kinsfolk are born to share adversity.
20Àá 17:18 It is senseless to give a pledge, to become surety for a neighbor.
20Àá 17:19 One who loves transgression loves strife; one who builds a high threshold invites broken bones.
20Àá 17:20 The crooked of mind do not prosper, and the perverse of tongue fall into calamity.
20Àá 17:21 The one who begets a fool gets trouble; the parent of a fool has no joy.
20Àá 17:22 A cheerful heart is a good medicine, but a downcast spirit dries up the bones.
20Àá 17:23 The wicked accept a concealed bribe to pervert the ways of justice.
20Àá 17:24 The discerning person looks to wisdom, but the eyes of a fool to the ends of the earth.
20Àá 17:25 Foolish children are a grief to their father and bitterness to her who bore them.
20Àá 17:26 To impose a fine on the innocent is not right, or to flog the noble for their integrity.
20Àá 17:27 One who spares words is knowledgeable; one who is cool in spirit has understanding.
20Àá 17:28 Even fools who keep silent are considered wise; when they close their lips, they are deemed intelligent.
20Àá 18:1 The one who lives alone is self-indulgent, showing contempt for all who have sound judgment.
20Àá 18:2 A fool takes no pleasure in understanding, but only in expressing personal opinion.
20Àá 18:3 When wickedness comes, contempt comes also; and with dishonor comes disgrace.
20Àá 18:4 The words of the mouth are deep waters; the fountain of wisdom is a gushing stream.
20Àá 18:5 It is not right to be partial to the guilty, or to subvert the innocent in judgment.
20Àá 18:6 A fool's lips bring strife, and a fool's mouth invites a flogging.
20Àá 18:7 The mouths of fools are their ruin, and their lips a snare to themselves.
20Àá 18:8 The words of a whisperer are like delicious morsels; they go down into the inner parts of the body.
20Àá 18:9 One who is slack in work is close kin to a vandal.
20Àá 18:10 The name of the LORD is a strong tower; the righteous run into it and are safe.
20Àá 18:11 The wealth of the rich is their strong city; in their imagination it is like a high wall.
20Àá 18:12 Before destruction one's heart is haughty, but humility goes before honor.
20Àá 18:13 If one gives answer before hearing, it is folly and shame.
20Àá 18:14 The human spirit will endure sickness; but a broken spirit--who can bear?
20Àá 18:15 An intelligent mind acquires knowledge, and the ear of the wise seeks knowledge.
20Àá 18:16 A gift opens doors; it gives access to the great.
20Àá 18:17 The one who first states a case seems right, until the other comes and cross-examines.
20Àá 18:18 Casting the lot puts an end to disputes and decides between powerful contenders.
20Àá 18:19 An ally offended is stronger than a city; such quarreling is like the bars of a castle.
20Àá 18:20 From the fruit of the mouth one's stomach is satisfied; the yield of the lips brings satisfaction.
20Àá 18:21 Death and life are in the power of the tongue, and those who love it will eat its fruits.
20Àá 18:22 He who finds a wife finds a good thing, and obtains favor from the LORD.
20Àá 18:23 The poor use entreaties, but the rich answer roughly.
20Àá 18:24 Some friends play at friendship but a true friend sticks closer than one's nearest kin.
20Àá 19:1 Better the poor walking in integrity than one perverse of speech who is a fool.
20Àá 19:2 Desire without knowledge is not good, and one who moves too hurriedly misses the way.
20Àá 19:3 One's own folly leads to ruin, yet the heart rages against the LORD.
20Àá 19:4 Wealth brings many friends, but the poor are left friendless.
20Àá 19:5 A false witness will not go unpunished, and a liar will not escape.
20Àá 19:6 Many seek the favor of the generous, and everyone is a friend to a giver of gifts.
20Àá 19:7 If the poor are hated even by their kin, how much more are they shunned by their friends! When they call after them, they are not there.
20Àá 19:8 To get wisdom is to love oneself; to keep understanding is to prosper.
20Àá 19:9 A false witness will not go unpunished, and the liar will perish.
20Àá 19:10 It is not fitting for a fool to live in luxury, much less for a slave to rule over princes.
20Àá 19:11 Those with good sense are slow to anger, and it is their glory to overlook an offense.
20Àá 19:12 A king's anger is like the growling of a lion, but his favor is like dew on the grass.
20Àá 19:13 A stupid child is ruin to a father, and a wife's quarreling is a continual dripping of rain.
20Àá 19:14 House and wealth are inherited from parents, but a prudent wife is from the LORD.
20Àá 19:15 Laziness brings on deep sleep; an idle person will suffer hunger.
20Àá 19:16 Those who keep the commandment will live; those who are heedless of their ways will die.
20Àá 19:17 Whoever is kind to the poor lends to the LORD, and will be repaid in full.
20Àá 19:18 Discipline your children while there is hope; do not set your heart on their destruction.
20Àá 19:19 A violent tempered person will pay the penalty; if you effect a rescue, you will only have to do it again.
20Àá 19:20 Listen to advice and accept instruction, that you may gain wisdom for the future.
20Àá 19:21 The human mind may devise many plans, but it is the purpose of the LORD that will be established.
20Àá 19:22 What is desirable in a person is loyalty, and it is better to be poor than a liar.
20Àá 19:23 The fear of the LORD is life indeed; filled with it one rests secure and suffers no harm.
20Àá 19:24 The lazy person buries a hand in the dish, and will not even bring it back to the mouth.
20Àá 19:25 Strike a scoffer, and the simple will learn prudence; reprove the intelligent, and they will gain knowledge.
20Àá 19:26 Those who do violence to their father and chase away their mother are children who cause shame and bring reproach.
20Àá 19:27 Cease straying, my child, from the words of knowledge, in order that you may hear instruction.
20Àá 19:28 A worthless witness mocks at justice, and the mouth of the wicked devours iniquity.
20Àá 19:29 Condemnation is ready for scoffers, and flogging for the backs of fools.
20Àá 20:1 Wine is a mocker, strong drink a brawler, and whoever is led astray by it is not wise.
20Àá 20:2 The dread anger of a king is like the growling of a lion; anyone who provokes him to anger forfeits life itself.
20Àá 20:3 It is honorable to refrain from strife, but every fool is quick to quarrel.
20Àá 20:4 The lazy person does not plow in season; harvest comes, and there is nothing to be found.
20Àá 20:5 The purposes in the human mind are like deep water, but the intelligent will draw them out.
20Àá 20:6 Many proclaim themselves loyal, but who can find one worthy of trust?
20Àá 20:7 The righteous walk in integrity--happy are the children who follow them!
20Àá 20:8 A king who sits on the throne of judgment winnows all evil with his eyes.
20Àá 20:9 Who can say, "I have made my heart clean; I am pure from my sin"?
20Àá 20:10 Diverse weights and diverse measures are both alike an abomination to the LORD.
20Àá 20:11 Even children make themselves known by their acts, by whether what they do is pure and right.
20Àá 20:12 The hearing ear and the seeing eye--the LORD has made them both.
20Àá 20:13 Do not love sleep, or else you will come to poverty; open your eyes, and you will have plenty of bread.
20Àá 20:14 "Bad, bad," says the buyer, then goes away and boasts.
20Àá 20:15 There is gold, and abundance of costly stones; but the lips informed by knowledge are a precious jewel.
20Àá 20:16 Take the garment of one who has given surety for a stranger; seize the pledge given as surety for foreigners.
20Àá 20:17 Bread gained by deceit is sweet, but afterward the mouth will be full of gravel.
20Àá 20:18 Plans are established by taking advice; wage war by following wise guidance.
20Àá 20:19 A gossip reveals secrets; therefore do not associate with a babbler.
20Àá 20:20 If you curse father or mother, your lamp will go out in utter darkness.
20Àá 20:21 An estate quickly acquired in the beginning will not be blessed in the end.
20Àá 20:22 Do not say, "I will repay evil"; wait for the LORD, and he will help you.
20Àá 20:23 Differing weights are an abomination to the LORD, and false scales are not good.
20Àá 20:24 All our steps are ordered by the LORD; how then can we understand our own ways?
20Àá 20:25 It is a snare for one to say rashly, "It is holy," and begin to reflect only after making a vow.
20Àá 20:26 A wise king winnows the wicked, and drives the wheel over them.
20Àá 20:27 The human spirit is the lamp of the LORD, searching every innermost part.
20Àá 20:28 Loyalty and faithfulness preserve the king, and his throne is upheld by righteousness.
20Àá 20:29 The glory of youths is their strength, but the beauty of the aged is their gray hair.
20Àá 20:30 Blows that wound cleanse away evil; beatings make clean the innermost parts.
20Àá 21:1 The king's heart is a stream of water in the hand of the LORD; he turns it wherever he will.
20Àá 21:2 All deeds are right in the sight of the doer, but the LORD weighs the heart.
20Àá 21:3 To do righteousness and justice is more acceptable to the LORD than sacrifice.
20Àá 21:4 Haughty eyes and a proud heart--the lamp of the wicked--are sin.
20Àá 21:5 The plans of the diligent lead surely to abundance, but everyone who is hasty comes only to want.
20Àá 21:6 The getting of treasures by a lying tongue is a fleeting vapor and a snare of death.
20Àá 21:7 The violence of the wicked will sweep them away, because they refuse to do what is just.
20Àá 21:8 The way of the guilty is crooked, but the conduct of the pure is right.
20Àá 21:9 It is better to live in a corner of the housetop than in a house shared with a contentious wife.
20Àá 21:10 The souls of the wicked desire evil; their neighbors find no mercy in their eyes.
20Àá 21:11 When a scoffer is punished, the simple become wiser; when the wise are instructed, they increase in knowledge.
20Àá 21:12 The Righteous One observes the house of the wicked; he casts the wicked down to ruin.
20Àá 21:13 If you close your ear to the cry of the poor, you will cry out and not be heard.
20Àá 21:14 A gift in secret averts anger; and a concealed bribe in the bosom, strong wrath.
20Àá 21:15 When justice is done, it is a joy to the righteous, but dismay to evildoers.
20Àá 21:16 Whoever wanders from the way of understanding will rest in the assembly of the dead.
20Àá 21:17 Whoever loves pleasure will suffer want; whoever loves wine and oil will not be rich.
20Àá 21:18 The wicked is a ransom for the righteous, and the faithless for the upright.
20Àá 21:19 It is better to live in a desert land than with a contentious and fretful wife.
20Àá 21:20 Precious treasure remains in the house of the wise, but the fool devours it.
20Àá 21:21 Whoever pursues righteousness and kindness will find life and honor.
20Àá 21:22 One wise person went up against a city of warriors and brought down the stronghold in which they trusted.
20Àá 21:23 To watch over mouth and tongue is to keep out of trouble.
20Àá 21:24 The proud, haughty person, named "Scoffer," acts with arrogant pride.
20Àá 21:25 The craving of the lazy person is fatal, for lazy hands refuse to labor.
20Àá 21:26 All day long the wicked covet, but the righteous give and do not hold back.
20Àá 21:27 The sacrifice of the wicked is an abomination; how much more when brought with evil intent.
20Àá 21:28 A false witness will perish, but a good listener will testify successfully.
20Àá 21:29 The wicked put on a bold face, but the upright give thought to their ways.
20Àá 21:30 No wisdom, no understanding, no counsel, can avail against the LORD.
20Àá 21:31 The horse is made ready for the day of battle, but the victory belongs to the LORD.
20Àá 22:1 A good name is to be chosen rather than great riches, and favor is better than silver or gold.
20Àá 22:2 The rich and the poor have this in common: the LORD is the maker of them all.
20Àá 22:3 The clever see danger and hide; but the simple go on, and suffer for it.
20Àá 22:4 The reward for humility and fear of the LORD is riches and honor and life.
20Àá 22:5 Thorns and snares are in the way of the perverse; the cautious will keep far from them.
20Àá 22:6 Train children in the right way, and when old, they will not stray.
20Àá 22:7 The rich rules over the poor, and the borrower is the slave of the lender.
20Àá 22:8 Whoever sows injustice will reap calamity, and the rod of anger will fail.
20Àá 22:9 Those who are generous are blessed, for they share their bread with the poor.
20Àá 22:10 Drive out a scoffer, and strife goes out; quarreling and abuse will cease.
20Àá 22:11 Those who love a pure heart and are gracious in speech will have the king as a friend.
20Àá 22:12 The eyes of the LORD keep watch over knowledge, but he overthrows the words of the faithless.
20Àá 22:13 The lazy person says, "There is a lion outside! I shall be killed in the streets!"
20Àá 22:14 The mouth of a loose woman is a deep pit; he with whom the LORD is angry falls into it.
20Àá 22:15 Folly is bound up in the heart of a boy, but the rod of discipline drives it far away.
20Àá 22:16 Oppressing the poor in order to enrich oneself, and giving to the rich, will lead only to loss.
20Àá 22:17 The words of the wise: Incline your ear and hear my words, and apply your mind to my teaching;
20Àá 22:18 for it will be pleasant if you keep them within you, if all of them are ready on your lips.
20Àá 22:19 So that your trust may be in the LORD, I have made them known to you today--yes, to you.
20Àá 22:20 Have I not written for you thirty sayings of admonition and knowledge,
20Àá 22:21 to show you what is right and true, so that you may give a true answer to those who sent you?
20Àá 22:22 Do not rob the poor because they are poor, or crush the afflicted at the gate;
20Àá 22:23 for the LORD pleads their cause and despoils of life those who despoil them.
20Àá 22:24 Make no friends with those given to anger, and do not associate with hotheads,
20Àá 22:25 or you may learn their ways and entangle yourself in a snare.
20Àá 22:26 Do not be one of those who give pledges, who become surety for debts.
20Àá 22:27 If you have nothing with which to pay, why should your bed be taken from under you?
20Àá 22:28 Do not remove the ancient landmark that your ancestors set up.
20Àá 22:29 Do you see those who are skillful in their work? they will serve kings; they will not serve common people.
20Àá 23:1 When you sit down to eat with a ruler, observe carefully what is before you,
20Àá 23:2 and put a knife to your throat if you have a big appetite.
20Àá 23:3 Do not desire the ruler's delicacies, for they are deceptive food.
20Àá 23:4 Do not wear yourself out to get rich; be wise enough to desist.
20Àá 23:5 When your eyes light upon it, it is gone; for suddenly it takes wings to itself, flying like an eagle toward heaven.
20Àá 23:6 Do not eat the bread of the stingy; do not desire their delicacies;
20Àá 23:7 for like a hair in the throat, so are they. "Eat and drink!" they say to you; but they do not mean it.
20Àá 23:8 You will vomit up the little you have eaten, and you will waste your pleasant words.
20Àá 23:9 Do not speak in the hearing of a fool, who will only despise the wisdom of your words.
20Àá 23:10 Do not remove an ancient landmark or encroach on the fields of orphans,
20Àá 23:11 for their redeemer is strong; he will plead their cause against you.
20Àá 23:12 Apply your mind to instruction and your ear to words of knowledge.
20Àá 23:13 Do not withhold discipline from your children; if you beat them with a rod, they will not die.
20Àá 23:14 If you beat them with the rod, you will save their lives from Sheol.
20Àá 23:15 My child, if your heart is wise, my heart too will be glad.
20Àá 23:16 My soul will rejoice when your lips speak what is right.
20Àá 23:17 Do not let your heart envy sinners, but always continue in the fear of the LORD.
20Àá 23:18 Surely there is a future, and your hope will not be cut off.
20Àá 23:19 Hear, my child, and be wise, and direct your mind in the way.
20Àá 23:20 Do not be among winebibbers, or among gluttonous eaters of meat;
20Àá 23:21 for the drunkard and the glutton will come to poverty, and drowsiness will clothe them with rags.
20Àá 23:22 Listen to your father who begot you, and do not despise your mother when she is old.
20Àá 23:23 Buy truth, and do not sell it; buy wisdom, instruction, and understanding.
20Àá 23:24 The father of the righteous will greatly rejoice; he who begets a wise son will be glad in him.
20Àá 23:25 Let your father and mother be glad; let her who bore you rejoice.
20Àá 23:26 My child, give me your heart, and let your eyes observe my ways.
20Àá 23:27 For a prostitute is a deep pit; an adulteress is a narrow well.
20Àá 23:28 She lies in wait like a robber and increases the number of the faithless.
20Àá 23:29 Who has woe? Who has sorrow? Who has strife? Who has complaining? Who has wounds without cause? Who has redness of eyes?
20Àá 23:30 Those who linger late over wine, those who keep trying mixed wines.
20Àá 23:31 Do not look at wine when it is red, when it sparkles in the cup and goes down smoothly.
20Àá 23:32 At the last it bites like a serpent, and stings like an adder.
20Àá 23:33 Your eyes will see strange things, and your mind utter perverse things.
20Àá 23:34 You will be like one who lies down in the midst of the sea, like one who lies on the top of a mast.
20Àá 23:35 "They struck me," you will say, "but I was not hurt; they beat me, but I did not feel it. When shall I awake? I will seek another drink."
20Àá 24:1 Do not envy the wicked, nor desire to be with them;
20Àá 24:2 for their minds devise violence, and their lips talk of mischief.
20Àá 24:3 By wisdom a house is built, and by understanding it is established;
20Àá 24:4 by knowledge the rooms are filled with all precious and pleasant riches.
20Àá 24:5 Wise warriors are mightier than strong ones, and those who have knowledge than those who have strength;
20Àá 24:6 for by wise guidance you can wage your war, and in abundance of counselors there is victory.
20Àá 24:7 Wisdom is too high for fools; in the gate they do not open their mouths.
20Àá 24:8 Whoever plans to do evil will be called a mischief-maker.
20Àá 24:9 The devising of folly is sin, and the scoffer is an abomination to all.
20Àá 24:10 If you faint in the day of adversity, your strength being small;
20Àá 24:11 if you hold back from rescuing those taken away to death, those who go staggering to the slaughter;
20Àá 24:12 if you say, "Look, we did not know this"--does not he who weighs the heart perceive it? Does not he who keeps watch over your soul know it? And will he not repay all according to their deeds?
20Àá 24:13 My child, eat honey, for it is good, and the drippings of the honeycomb are sweet to your taste.
20Àá 24:14 Know that wisdom is such to your soul; if you find it, you will find a future, and your hope will not be cut off.
20Àá 24:15 Do not lie in wait like an outlaw against the home of the righteous; do no violence to the place where the righteous live;
20Àá 24:16 for though they fall seven times, they will rise again; but the wicked are overthrown by calamity.
20Àá 24:17 Do not rejoice when your enemies fall, and do not let your heart be glad when they stumble,
20Àá 24:18 or else the LORD will see it and be displeased, and turn away his anger from them.
20Àá 24:19 Do not fret because of evildoers. Do not envy the wicked;
20Àá 24:20 for the evil have no future; the lamp of the wicked will go out.
20Àá 24:21 My child, fear the LORD and the king, and do not disobey either of them;
20Àá 24:22 for disaster comes from them suddenly, and who knows the ruin that both can bring?
20Àá 24:23 These also are sayings of the wise: Partiality in judging is not good.
20Àá 24:24 Whoever says to the wicked, "You are innocent," will be cursed by peoples, abhorred by nations;
20Àá 24:25 but those who rebuke the wicked will have delight, and a good blessing will come upon them.
20Àá 24:26 One who gives an honest answer gives a kiss on the lips.
20Àá 24:27 Prepare your work outside, get everything ready for you in the field; and after that build your house.
20Àá 24:28 Do not be a witness against your neighbor without cause, and do not deceive with your lips.
20Àá 24:29 Do not say, "I will do to others as they have done to me; I will pay them back for what they have done."
20Àá 24:30 I passed by the field of one who was lazy, by the vineyard of a stupid person;
20Àá 24:31 and see, it was all overgrown with thorns; the ground was covered with nettles, and its stone wall was broken down.
20Àá 24:32 Then I saw and considered it; I looked and received instruction.
20Àá 24:33 A little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the hands to rest,
20Àá 24:34 and poverty will come upon you like a robber, and want, like an armed warrior.
20Àá 25:1 These are other proverbs of Solomon that the officials of King Hezekiah of Judah copied.
20Àá 25:2 It is the glory of God to conceal things, but the glory of kings is to search things out.
20Àá 25:3 Like the heavens for height, like the earth for depth, so the mind of kings is unsearchable.
20Àá 25:4 Take away the dross from the silver, and the smith has material for a vessel;
20Àá 25:5 take away the wicked from the presence of the king, and his throne will be established in righteousness.
20Àá 25:6 Do not put yourself forward in the king's presence or stand in the place of the great;
20Àá 25:7 for it is better to be told, "Come up here," than to be put lower in the presence of a noble. What your eyes have seen
20Àá 25:8 do not hastily bring into court; for what will you do in the end, when your neighbor puts you to shame?
20Àá 25:9 Argue your case with your neighbor directly, and do not disclose another's secret;
20Àá 25:10 or else someone who hears you will bring shame upon you, and your ill repute will have no end.
20Àá 25:11 A word fitly spoken is like apples of gold in a setting of silver.
20Àá 25:12 Like a gold ring or an ornament of gold is a wise rebuke to a listening ear.
20Àá 25:13 Like the cold of snow in the time of harvest are faithful messengers to those who send them; they refresh the spirit of their masters.
20Àá 25:14 Like clouds and wind without rain is one who boasts of a gift never given.
20Àá 25:15 With patience a ruler may be persuaded, and a soft tongue can break bones.
20Àá 25:16 If you have found honey, eat only enough for you, or else, having too much, you will vomit it.
20Àá 25:17 Let your foot be seldom in your neighbor's house, otherwise the neighbor will become weary of you and hate you.
20Àá 25:18 Like a war club, a sword, or a sharp arrow is one who bears false witness against a neighbor.
20Àá 25:19 Like a bad tooth or a lame foot is trust in a faithless person in time of trouble.
20Àá 25:20 Like vinegar on a wound is one who sings songs to a heavy heart. Like a moth in clothing or a worm in wood, sorrow gnaws at the human heart.
20Àá 25:21 If your enemies are hungry, give them bread to eat; and if they are thirsty, give them water to drink;
20Àá 25:22 for you will heap coals of fire on their heads, and the LORD will reward you.
20Àá 25:23 The north wind produces rain, and a backbiting tongue, angry looks.
20Àá 25:24 It is better to live in a corner of the housetop than in a house shared with a contentious wife.
20Àá 25:25 Like cold water to a thirsty soul, so is good news from a far country.
20Àá 25:26 Like a muddied spring or a polluted fountain are the righteous who give way before the wicked.
20Àá 25:27 It is not good to eat much honey, or to seek honor on top of honor.
20Àá 25:28 Like a city breached, without walls, is one who lacks self-control.
20Àá 26:1 Like snow in summer or rain in harvest, so honor is not fitting for a fool.
20Àá 26:2 Like a sparrow in its flitting, like a swallow in its flying, an undeserved curse goes nowhere.
20Àá 26:3 A whip for the horse, a bridle for the donkey, and a rod for the back of fools.
20Àá 26:4 Do not answer fools according to their folly, or you will be a fool yourself.
20Àá 26:5 Answer fools according to their folly, or they will be wise in their own eyes.
20Àá 26:6 It is like cutting off one's foot and drinking down violence, to send a message by a fool.
20Àá 26:7 The legs of a disabled person hang limp; so does a proverb in the mouth of a fool.
20Àá 26:8 It is like binding a stone in a sling to give honor to a fool.
20Àá 26:9 Like a thornbush brandished by the hand of a drunkard is a proverb in the mouth of a fool.
20Àá 26:10 Like an archer who wounds everybody is one who hires a passing fool or drunkard.
20Àá 26:11 Like a dog that returns to its vomit is a fool who reverts to his folly.
20Àá 26:12 Do you see persons wise in their own eyes? There is more hope for fools than for them.
20Àá 26:13 The lazy person says, "There is a lion in the road! There is a lion in the streets!"
20Àá 26:14 As a door turns on its hinges, so does a lazy person in bed.
20Àá 26:15 The lazy person buries a hand in the dish, and is too tired to bring it back to the mouth.
20Àá 26:16 The lazy person is wiser in self-esteem than seven who can answer discreetly.
20Àá 26:17 Like somebody who takes a passing dog by the ears is one who meddles in the quarrel of another.
20Àá 26:18 Like a maniac who shoots deadly firebrands and arrows,
20Àá 26:19 so is one who deceives a neighbor and says, "I am only joking!"
20Àá 26:20 For lack of wood the fire goes out, and where there is no whisperer, quarreling ceases.
20Àá 26:21 As charcoal is to hot embers and wood to fire, so is a quarrelsome person for kindling strife.
20Àá 26:22 The words of a whisperer are like delicious morsels; they go down into the inner parts of the body.
20Àá 26:23 Like the glaze covering an earthen vessel are smooth lips with an evil heart.
20Àá 26:24 An enemy dissembles in speaking while harboring deceit within;
20Àá 26:25 when an enemy speaks graciously, do not believe it, for there are seven abominations concealed within;
20Àá 26:26 though hatred is covered with guile, the enemy's wickedness will be exposed in the assembly.
20Àá 26:27 Whoever digs a pit will fall into it, and a stone will come back on the one who starts it rolling.
20Àá 26:28 A lying tongue hates its victims, and a flattering mouth works ruin.
20Àá 27:1 Do not boast about tomorrow, for you do not know what a day may bring.
20Àá 27:2 Let another praise you, and not your own mouth--a stranger, and not your own lips.
20Àá 27:3 A stone is heavy, and sand is weighty, but a fool's provocation is heavier than both.
20Àá 27:4 Wrath is cruel, anger is overwhelming, but who is able to stand before jealousy?
20Àá 27:5 Better is open rebuke than hidden love.
20Àá 27:6 Well meant are the wounds a friend inflicts, but profuse are the kisses of an enemy.
20Àá 27:7 The sated appetite spurns honey, but to a ravenous appetite even the bitter is sweet.
20Àá 27:8 Like a bird that strays from its nest is one who strays from home.
20Àá 27:9 Perfume and incense make the heart glad, but the soul is torn by trouble.
20Àá 27:10 Do not forsake your friend or the friend of your parent; do not go to the house of your kindred in the day of your calamity. Better is a neighbor who is nearby than kindred who are far away.
20Àá 27:11 Be wise, my child, and make my heart glad, so that I may answer whoever reproaches me.
20Àá 27:12 The clever see danger and hide; but the simple go on, and suffer for it.
20Àá 27:13 Take the garment of one who has given surety for a stranger; seize the pledge given as surety for foreigners.
20Àá 27:14 Whoever blesses a neighbor with a loud voice, rising early in the morning, will be counted as cursing.
20Àá 27:15 A continual dripping on a rainy day and a contentious wife are alike;
20Àá 27:16 to restrain her is to restrain the wind or to grasp oil in the right hand.
20Àá 27:17 Iron sharpens iron, and one person sharpens the wits of another.
20Àá 27:18 Anyone who tends a fig tree will eat its fruit, and anyone who takes care of a master will be honored.
20Àá 27:19 Just as water reflects the face, so one human heart reflects another.
20Àá 27:20 Sheol and Abaddon are never satisfied, and human eyes are never satisfied.
20Àá 27:21 The crucible is for silver, and the furnace is for gold, so a person is tested by being praised.
20Àá 27:22 Crush a fool in a mortar with a pestle along with crushed grain, but the folly will not be driven out.
20Àá 27:23 Know well the condition of your flocks, and give attention to your herds;
20Àá 27:24 for riches do not last forever, nor a crown for all generations.
20Àá 27:25 When the grass is gone, and new growth appears, and the herbage of the mountains is gathered,
20Àá 27:26 the lambs will provide your clothing, and the goats the price of a field;
20Àá 27:27 there will be enough goats' milk for your food, for the food of your household and nourishment for your servant girls.
20Àá 28:1 The wicked flee when no one pursues, but the righteous are as bold as a lion.
20Àá 28:2 When a land rebels it has many rulers; but with an intelligent ruler there is lasting order.
20Àá 28:3 A ruler who oppresses the poor is a beating rain that leaves no food.
20Àá 28:4 Those who forsake the law praise the wicked, but those who keep the law struggle against them.
20Àá 28:5 The evil do not understand justice, but those who seek the LORD understand it completely.
20Àá 28:6 Better to be poor and walk in integrity than to be crooked in one's ways even though rich.
20Àá 28:7 Those who keep the law are wise children, but companions of gluttons shame their parents.
20Àá 28:8 One who augments wealth by exorbitant interest gathers it for another who is kind to the poor.
20Àá 28:9 When one will not listen to the law, even one's prayers are an abomination.
20Àá 28:10 Those who mislead the upright into evil ways will fall into pits of their own making, but the blameless will have a goodly inheritance.
20Àá 28:11 The rich is wise in self-esteem, but an intelligent poor person sees through the pose.
20Àá 28:12 When the righteous triumph, there is great glory, but when the wicked prevail, people go into hiding.
20Àá 28:13 No one who conceals transgressions will prosper, but one who confesses and forsakes them will obtain mercy.
20Àá 28:14 Happy is the one who is never without fear, but one who is hard-hearted will fall into calamity.
20Àá 28:15 Like a roaring lion or a charging bear is a wicked ruler over a poor people.
20Àá 28:16 A ruler who lacks understanding is a cruel oppressor; but one who hates unjust gain will enjoy a long life.
20Àá 28:17 If someone is burdened with the blood of another, let that killer be a fugitive until death; let no one offer assistance.
20Àá 28:18 One who walks in integrity will be safe, but whoever follows crooked ways will fall into the Pit.
20Àá 28:19 Anyone who tills the land will have plenty of bread, but one who follows worthless pursuits will have plenty of poverty.
20Àá 28:20 The faithful will abound with blessings, but one who is in a hurry to be rich will not go unpunished.
20Àá 28:21 To show partiality is not good--yet for a piece of bread a person may do wrong.
20Àá 28:22 The miser is in a hurry to get rich and does not know that loss is sure to come.
20Àá 28:23 Whoever rebukes a person will afterward find more favor than one who flatters with the tongue.
20Àá 28:24 Anyone who robs father or mother and says, "That is no crime," is partner to a thug.
20Àá 28:25 The greedy person stirs up strife, but whoever trusts in the LORD will be enriched.
20Àá 28:26 Those who trust in their own wits are fools; but those who walk in wisdom come through safely.
20Àá 28:27 Whoever gives to the poor will lack nothing, but one who turns a blind eye will get many a curse.
20Àá 28:28 When the wicked prevail, people go into hiding; but when they perish, the righteous increase.
20Àá 29:1 One who is often reproved, yet remains stubborn, will suddenly be broken beyond healing.
20Àá 29:2 When the righteous are in authority, the people rejoice; but when the wicked rule, the people groan.
20Àá 29:3 A child who loves wisdom makes a parent glad, but to keep company with prostitutes is to squander one's substance.
20Àá 29:4 By justice a king gives stability to the land, but one who makes heavy exactions ruins it.
20Àá 29:5 Whoever flatters a neighbor is spreading a net for the neighbor's feet.
20Àá 29:6 In the transgression of the evil there is a snare, but the righteous sing and rejoice.
20Àá 29:7 The righteous know the rights of the poor; the wicked have no such understanding.
20Àá 29:8 Scoffers set a city aflame, but the wise turn away wrath.
20Àá 29:9 If the wise go to law with fools, there is ranting and ridicule without relief.
20Àá 29:10 The bloodthirsty hate the blameless, and they seek the life of the upright.
20Àá 29:11 A fool gives full vent to anger, but the wise quietly holds it back.
20Àá 29:12 If a ruler listens to falsehood, all his officials will be wicked.
20Àá 29:13 The poor and the oppressor have this in common: the LORD gives light to the eyes of both.
20Àá 29:14 If a king judges the poor with equity, his throne will be established forever.
20Àá 29:15 The rod and reproof give wisdom, but a mother is disgraced by a neglected child.
20Àá 29:16 When the wicked are in authority, transgression increases, but the righteous will look upon their downfall.
20Àá 29:17 Discipline your children, and they will give you rest; they will give delight to your heart.
20Àá 29:18 Where there is no prophecy, the people cast off restraint, but happy are those who keep the law.
20Àá 29:19 By mere words servants are not disciplined, for though they understand, they will not give heed.
20Àá 29:20 Do you see someone who is hasty in speech? There is more hope for a fool than for anyone like that.
20Àá 29:21 A slave pampered from childhood will come to a bad end.
20Àá 29:22 One given to anger stirs up strife, and the hothead causes much transgression.
20Àá 29:23 A person's pride will bring humiliation, but one who is lowly in spirit will obtain honor.
20Àá 29:24 To be a partner of a thief is to hate one's own life; one hears the victim's curse, but discloses nothing.
20Àá 29:25 The fear of others lays a snare, but one who trusts in the LORD is secure.
20Àá 29:26 Many seek the favor of a ruler, but it is from the LORD that one gets justice.
20Àá 29:27 The unjust are an abomination to the righteous, but the upright are an abomination to the wicked.
20Àá 30:1 The words of Agur son of Jakeh. An oracle. Thus says the man: I am weary, O God, I am weary, O God. How can I prevail?
20Àá 30:2 Surely I am too stupid to be human; I do not have human understanding.
20Àá 30:3 I have not learned wisdom, nor have I knowledge of the holy ones.
20Àá 30:4 Who has ascended to heaven and come down? Who has gathered the wind in the hollow of the hand? Who has wrapped up the waters in a garment? Who has established all the ends of the earth? What is the person's name? And what is the name of the person's child? Surely you know!
20Àá 30:5 Every word of God proves true; he is a shield to those who take refuge in him.
20Àá 30:6 Do not add to his words, or else he will rebuke you, and you will be found a liar.
20Àá 30:7 Two things I ask of you; do not deny them to me before I die:
20Àá 30:8 Remove far from me falsehood and lying; give me neither poverty nor riches; feed me with the food that I need,
20Àá 30:9 or I shall be full, and deny you, and say, "Who is the LORD?" or I shall be poor, and steal, and profane the name of my God.
20Àá 30:10 Do not slander a servant to a master, or the servant will curse you, and you will be held guilty.
20Àá 30:11 There are those who curse their fathers and do not bless their mothers.
20Àá 30:12 There are those who are pure in their own eyes yet are not cleansed of their filthiness.
20Àá 30:13 There are those--how lofty are their eyes, how high their eyelids lift!
20Àá 30:14 There are those whose teeth are swords, whose teeth are knives, to devour the poor from off the earth, the needy from among mortals.
20Àá 30:15 The leech has two daughters; "Give, give," they cry. Three things are never satisfied; four never say, "Enough":
20Àá 30:16 Sheol, the barren womb, the earth ever thirsty for water, and the fire that never says, "Enough."
20Àá 30:17 The eye that mocks a father and scorns to obey a mother will be pecked out by the ravens of the valley and eaten by the vultures.
20Àá 30:18 Three things are too wonderful for me; four I do not understand:
20Àá 30:19 the way of an eagle in the sky, the way of a snake on a rock, the way of a ship on the high seas, and the way of a man with a girl.
20Àá 30:20 This is the way of an adulteress: she eats, and wipes her mouth, and says, "I have done no wrong."
20Àá 30:21 Under three things the earth trembles; under four it cannot bear up:
20Àá 30:22 a slave when he becomes king, and a fool when glutted with food;
20Àá 30:23 an unloved woman when she gets a husband, and a maid when she succeeds her mistress.
20Àá 30:24 Four things on earth are small, yet they are exceedingly wise:
20Àá 30:25 the ants are a people without strength, yet they provide their food in the summer;
20Àá 30:26 the badgers are a people without power, yet they make their homes in the rocks;
20Àá 30:27 the locusts have no king, yet all of them march in rank;
20Àá 30:28 the lizard can be grasped in the hand, yet it is found in kings' palaces.
20Àá 30:29 Three things are stately in their stride; four are stately in their gait:
20Àá 30:30 the lion, which is mightiest among wild animals and does not turn back before any;
20Àá 30:31 the strutting rooster, the he-goat, and a king striding before his people.
20Àá 30:32 If you have been foolish, exalting yourself, or if you have been devising evil, put your hand on your mouth.
20Àá 30:33 For as pressing milk produces curds, and pressing the nose produces blood, so pressing anger produces strife.
20Àá 31:1 The words of King Lemuel. An oracle that his mother taught him:
20Àá 31:2 No, my son! No, son of my womb! No, son of my vows!
20Àá 31:3 Do not give your strength to women, your ways to those who destroy kings.
20Àá 31:4 It is not for kings, O Lemuel, it is not for kings to drink wine, or for rulers to desire strong drink;
20Àá 31:5 or else they will drink and forget what has been decreed, and will pervert the rights of all the afflicted.
20Àá 31:6 Give strong drink to one who is perishing, and wine to those in bitter distress;
20Àá 31:7 let them drink and forget their poverty, and remember their misery no more.
20Àá 31:8 Speak out for those who cannot speak, for the rights of all the destitute.
20Àá 31:9 Speak out, judge righteously, defend the rights of the poor and needy.
20Àá 31:10 A capable wife who can find? She is far more precious than jewels.
20Àá 31:11 The heart of her husband trusts in her, and he will have no lack of gain.
20Àá 31:12 She does him good, and not harm, all the days of her life.
20Àá 31:13 She seeks wool and flax, and works with willing hands.
20Àá 31:14 She is like the ships of the merchant, she brings her food from far away.
20Àá 31:15 She rises while it is still night and provides food for her household and tasks for her servant girls.
20Àá 31:16 She considers a field and buys it; with the fruit of her hands she plants a vineyard.
20Àá 31:17 She girds herself with strength, and makes her arms strong.
20Àá 31:18 She perceives that her merchandise is profitable. Her lamp does not go out at night.
20Àá 31:19 She puts her hands to the distaff, and her hands hold the spindle.
20Àá 31:20 She opens her hand to the poor, and reaches out her hands to the needy.
20Àá 31:21 She is not afraid for her household when it snows, for all her household are clothed in crimson.
20Àá 31:22 She makes herself coverings; her clothing is fine linen and purple.
20Àá 31:23 Her husband is known in the city gates, taking his seat among the elders of the land.
20Àá 31:24 She makes linen garments and sells them; she supplies the merchant with sashes.
20Àá 31:25 Strength and dignity are her clothing, and she laughs at the time to come.
20Àá 31:26 She opens her mouth with wisdom, and the teaching of kindness is on her tongue.
20Àá 31:27 She looks well to the ways of her household, and does not eat the bread of idleness.
20Àá 31:28 Her children rise up and call her happy; her husband too, and he praises her:
20Àá 31:29 "Many women have done excellently, but you surpass them all."
20Àá 31:30 Charm is deceitful, and beauty is vain, but a woman who fears the LORD is to be praised.
20Àá 31:31 Give her a share in the fruit of her hands, and let her works praise her in the city gates.
